WEBVTT

00:43.560 --> 00:45.950
[instrumental music]

01:11.720 --> 01:13.630
[sighs]

01:15.510 --> 01:16.780
Man on TV:
War continues in Europe.

01:16.980 --> 01:18.300
Hitler has suggested
that any questions

01:18.500 --> 01:20.610
over the future of Poland
will be settled entirely

01:20.810 --> 01:22.560
between Germany and Russia.

01:22.760 --> 01:24.040
He also stated that he regards

01:24.240 --> 01:26.350
the Czechoslovak Question
as closed.

01:26.550 --> 01:27.790
Speaking at Washington,

01:27.990 --> 01:29.920
President Roosevelt made
no comment as to...

01:30.120 --> 01:32.440
[upbeat music]

02:00.510 --> 02:02.940
[music continues]

02:31.930 --> 02:33.840
[music continues]

02:35.670 --> 02:37.410
Clare: The name's Cavendish.

02:41.420 --> 02:43.160
A Miss Cavendish.

02:47.160 --> 02:49.860
Perhaps it's a first name,
Cavendish?

02:53.520 --> 02:56.140
Um, cigarette?

02:56.340 --> 02:58.140
The cigarettes you keep
for your clients,

02:58.340 --> 03:00.100
are they better or worse than
what you smoke?

03:00.300 --> 03:01.790
They're the same.

03:04.140 --> 03:06.530
Perhaps it is a first name,
Cavendish.

03:07.970 --> 03:10.500
It's... a good first name.

03:10.700 --> 03:11.970
Mm.

03:16.150 --> 03:18.380
Please.

03:18.580 --> 03:22.850
How private exactly are your
investigations, Mr. Marlowe?

03:24.290 --> 03:27.650
What can I do for you,
Mrs. Cavendish?

03:27.850 --> 03:29.860
Mm, you are a detective.

03:31.340 --> 03:33.430
I'd like you
to find someone for me.

03:33.630 --> 03:34.520
Mm-hmm.

03:34.720 --> 03:36.220
Nico Peterson.

03:36.420 --> 03:41.010
He was my lover, he disappeared
without saying goodbye.

03:41.210 --> 03:44.180
When you say disappeared,
do you mean out of your life

03:44.380 --> 03:46.360
or out of the world?

03:46.560 --> 03:49.150
I don't know,
that's why I'm here.

03:49.350 --> 03:51.580
Where was your husband,
Mrs. Cavendish,

03:51.780 --> 03:54.980
when your lover Nico Peterson
disappeared?

03:55.180 --> 03:57.100
[sighs]
In retrospect...

03:59.100 --> 04:01.850
do call me Cavendish
without the Missus.

04:02.050 --> 04:03.600
I like it.

04:03.790 --> 04:05.550
Was your lover the sort of man
to disappear

04:05.750 --> 04:07.430
with you as a lover?

04:07.620 --> 04:09.990
Normally,
they don't disappear easily.

04:10.190 --> 04:12.600
Marlowe: No, I bet they don't.

04:12.800 --> 04:14.210
They stay around,

04:14.410 --> 04:17.570
climb trellises,
scenes in restaurants,

04:17.770 --> 04:20.350
lie down in the road,
promise you anything.

04:20.550 --> 04:22.050
Oh, I know how it goes.

04:22.250 --> 04:24.610
Do you lie down
in the road, Mr. Marlowe?

04:27.220 --> 04:29.090
- Drink?
- Please.

04:32.920 --> 04:36.110
Well, he's tall, like you.

04:36.310 --> 04:37.620
Bit of a weaker man.

04:38.750 --> 04:41.620
He dresses nice, meticulously.

04:43.150 --> 04:45.250
What does that say about a man?

04:45.450 --> 04:47.860
Does Mr. Peterson get money
from his profession

04:48.060 --> 04:51.380
or does he just
profess his profession?

04:51.580 --> 04:53.650
You seem to assume
that I was involved

04:53.840 --> 04:56.520
with someone unsuitable.

04:56.720 --> 04:59.640
Yes, unless you were
unsuitable for him.

05:02.040 --> 05:04.130
Go to hell,
you pathetic little...

05:04.330 --> 05:06.700
<i>Marlowe: Would it be accurate</i>
<i>to say that Mr. Peterson</i>

05:06.900 --> 05:09.880
<i>would be a marginal person</i>
<i>in motion pictures?</i>

05:10.080 --> 05:11.750
- Apologies, sir.
- Yes. Alright.

05:11.950 --> 05:13.320
<i>Clare: It would be accurate,</i>

05:13.520 --> 05:15.280
<i>it would be</i>
<i>very accurate indeed.</i>

05:15.480 --> 05:16.750
Man 1: Go to hell,
you pathetic...

05:21.050 --> 05:22.760
<i>Clare: We would meet</i>
<i>at the Corbata Club.</i>

05:22.960 --> 05:24.420
<i>Do you know it?</i>

05:24.610 --> 05:27.550
Marlowe: How did Mr. Peterson
know the Corbata Club?

05:27.750 --> 05:29.120
Was he your guest

05:29.310 --> 05:32.640
or the kind of guy
who was anybody's guest?

05:32.840 --> 05:35.110
My husband and I
have an arrangement.

05:36.980 --> 05:40.650
May I ask,
is your husband homosexual?

05:40.850 --> 05:43.090
[chuckles]

05:43.290 --> 05:47.000
No. He isn't remotely
that interesting.

05:47.200 --> 05:49.920
He likes polo,
alcohol, waitresses

05:50.120 --> 05:51.310
and my money.

05:51.510 --> 05:53.880
Marlowe: Your money,
Mrs. Cavendish?

05:54.080 --> 05:55.530
I beg your pardon, Mr. Marlowe.

05:55.730 --> 05:57.480
I'm asking if the
money is yours.

05:58.830 --> 06:02.320
My father was in oil,
he's dead.

06:02.520 --> 06:05.930
You'd know my mother,
but we won't discuss her now.

06:06.130 --> 06:09.940
Did you conduct your affair
with Mr. Peterson at the club?

06:10.140 --> 06:12.410
We weren't meeting
in the horse sheds, Mr. Marlowe.

06:14.110 --> 06:15.890
Marlowe:
What did he not show up for?

06:17.590 --> 06:19.030
An assignation.

06:19.230 --> 06:21.550
[instrumental music]

06:26.080 --> 06:29.130
<i>Clare: I telephoned him</i>
<i>a few times, no answer,</i>

06:29.330 --> 06:31.610
<i>and then I went to his house</i>
<i>the following week.</i>

06:31.810 --> 06:32.740
[door rattling]

06:32.940 --> 06:34.440
<i>The milk hadn't been canceled</i>

06:34.640 --> 06:36.920
<i>and the newspapers</i>
<i>were piled up on his porch.</i>

06:37.120 --> 06:39.100
[knock on door]

06:39.300 --> 06:41.710
<i>Marlowe: Did he have</i>
<i>things to hide?</i>

06:41.910 --> 06:43.800
<i>Clare: Haven't we all?</i>

06:44.000 --> 06:47.540
Marlowe: What do you think
has become of Mr. Peterson?

06:47.740 --> 06:49.940
Clare: Told you,
I want a set of fresh eyes

06:50.130 --> 06:53.370
and yours come
highly recommended.

06:53.570 --> 06:56.060
Maybe you'll find out
what I can't.

07:06.290 --> 07:10.080
My name's really Clare,
like the county.

07:12.560 --> 07:13.790
You know the county?

07:13.980 --> 07:16.880
Yeah, in Ireland.
I know it well.

07:17.070 --> 07:21.750
My mother was in pictures,
you'd know her.

07:21.950 --> 07:24.790
It's rather embarrassing
with the upper class.

07:27.400 --> 07:30.400
You're very perceptive
and sensitive, Mr. Marlowe.

07:35.360 --> 07:37.110
I imagine it gives you trouble.

07:37.310 --> 07:39.500
[instrumental music]

07:58.600 --> 08:00.480
[doorknob rattling]

08:16.580 --> 08:19.290
He ain't home, bo.

08:19.480 --> 08:23.290
What? He owe you dough
or make time with your wife?

08:23.490 --> 08:24.680
That's the way it is, huh?

08:24.880 --> 08:28.470
Yeah, I'd say so,
and good for him.

08:28.670 --> 08:32.900
He's not a bad guy, if you don't
trust people anyway. I don't.

08:34.600 --> 08:37.610
I think he's from Cleveland.

08:37.810 --> 08:39.480
That's my place
across the street,

08:39.680 --> 08:41.610
he used to come over sometimes,

08:41.810 --> 08:43.530
pass the time of day.

08:43.730 --> 08:45.660
Give me a smoke.

08:45.860 --> 08:48.490
How, uh, how long
has he been gone?

08:48.690 --> 08:51.530
Oh, I guess I last seen him
seven weeks ago.

08:52.830 --> 08:54.970
You, uh, you see him leave?

08:55.170 --> 08:57.840
No, I just noticed he was gone.

08:59.230 --> 09:01.500
How did you know?

09:01.700 --> 09:04.370
Well, he wasn't there anymore.

09:04.570 --> 09:07.030
That means there weren't any
women banging on his front door,

09:07.230 --> 09:09.940
or throwing a shoe at the house.

09:10.140 --> 09:13.990
I mean, I did pretty good
in my day, but not like him.

09:14.190 --> 09:15.860
Are you a cop?

09:16.060 --> 09:17.430
Sort of.

09:17.630 --> 09:20.390
A private dick ain't no cop.

09:20.590 --> 09:24.130
Yeah, you're not the first one
to come around asking about him.

09:24.330 --> 09:26.960
A pair of wetbacks
showed up last week,

09:27.160 --> 09:30.360
and they was all gussied up,
but a beaner in a suit

09:30.560 --> 09:32.880
and fancy necktie,
it's still a beaner, right?

09:33.080 --> 09:35.490
No, sometimes
he's the King of Spain.

09:35.690 --> 09:38.150
King of Spain don't ride
around in no Lincoln,

09:38.350 --> 09:40.320
with a Mexican re-spray.

09:40.520 --> 09:43.330
Yeah, I used to work in the low
end of the motor trade myself,

09:43.530 --> 09:45.550
it was two beaners in a hot car

09:45.750 --> 09:48.330
that had been across
the border and back.

09:48.530 --> 09:50.240
[engine revving]

09:54.370 --> 09:57.300
<i>Joe: Oh, let's start</i>
<i>at the beginning.</i>

09:57.500 --> 09:59.560
This guy's been looked at, sure.

09:59.760 --> 10:02.340
Grifts, alienations
of affection,

10:02.540 --> 10:05.830
parking tickets,
drunk at a social gathering.

10:06.030 --> 10:09.570
And in the early days,
public solicitation.

10:09.770 --> 10:11.140
Now nobody knew
he ever had a house,

10:11.340 --> 10:13.530
he's down as domicile unknown.

10:13.730 --> 10:15.050
He does have a house,
I was there.

10:15.250 --> 10:16.580
Yeah, well,
there's having a house

10:16.780 --> 10:18.540
and being the person paying
for it, I suppose.

10:18.730 --> 10:20.010
Who was paying for it?

10:20.210 --> 10:21.930
Well, I think you'll find
he was paying cash

10:22.130 --> 10:24.620
from his no visible
means of support.

10:31.150 --> 10:34.190
Hope the lady friend looking
for him looks good in black.

10:35.720 --> 10:38.120
He was killed.
October 22nd, hit and run.

10:38.320 --> 10:39.760
Outside the Corbata Club.

10:41.160 --> 10:42.650
You owe me lunch.

10:42.850 --> 10:44.600
Liquid or regular?

10:44.800 --> 10:47.220
[tires screeching]

10:47.420 --> 10:48.390
[tense music]

10:48.590 --> 10:50.090
[engine revving]

10:50.290 --> 10:51.920
"Deceased was struck
by a vehicle, make unknown,

10:52.120 --> 10:53.830
driver unknown,
on Bay Canyon Drive

10:54.030 --> 10:55.350
just outside the Corbata Club.

10:55.550 --> 10:57.010
Deceased has numerous
injuries including

10:57.210 --> 10:59.400
gross comminuted fracture
right side of his skull.

10:59.600 --> 11:00.840
Death be not proud."

11:01.040 --> 11:02.570
[engine revving]

11:04.530 --> 11:06.100
[tires screech]

11:16.710 --> 11:19.460
[suspenseful music]

11:24.770 --> 11:26.680
[dramatic music]

11:28.380 --> 11:30.470
[engine revving]

11:41.430 --> 11:43.450
I guess there's no point
in asking for an invite.

11:43.650 --> 11:45.060
Oh, none at all, sir.

11:45.260 --> 11:46.960
Uh-huh.

11:58.410 --> 12:00.060
Oh, hey!

12:04.460 --> 12:05.730
You looking for a gardening job?

12:05.930 --> 12:07.980
Actually, no,
a membership form.

12:09.510 --> 12:12.040
Albert. We've got
a hedge hopper here.

12:12.240 --> 12:13.550
He needs trimming.

12:14.690 --> 12:16.780
<i>A ver.</i>

12:16.980 --> 12:18.210
- Hey, buddy.
- <i>A ver.</i>

12:19.650 --> 12:21.310
[groans]

12:21.510 --> 12:23.960
[suspenseful music]

12:28.960 --> 12:32.710
Maybe there's a reason
you're unpopular with policemen.

12:32.910 --> 12:35.760
Keep getting, I don't know...

12:35.960 --> 12:38.890
punched, locked up,

12:39.090 --> 12:40.980
and almost,
but not quite, charged

12:41.180 --> 12:44.510
with accessory,
obstruction, etcetera.

12:44.710 --> 12:47.600
- And at your age.
- It's my manner, Joe.

12:47.800 --> 12:50.380
Yup, starting to wish
you still had your pension?

12:50.580 --> 12:52.300
Sure you are.

12:52.500 --> 12:55.870
Look, Marlowe, listen...

12:56.070 --> 12:58.380
This guy got killed after
getting sauced in there.

13:00.120 --> 13:01.570
The remains smelled
like a brewery,

13:01.770 --> 13:03.610
and he had marks
up and down his arms,

13:03.810 --> 13:05.440
his head popped like a pumpkin.

13:05.640 --> 13:07.090
The Corbata Club
likes to make it nice,

13:07.290 --> 13:08.660
it does not like trouble.

13:08.860 --> 13:10.710
Hit and run
is two crimes at least.

13:10.910 --> 13:12.190
Don't fuck with me,
this is LA.

13:12.390 --> 13:13.620
These guys like Peterson

13:13.820 --> 13:15.190
are a dime a dozen,
they come out here,

13:15.390 --> 13:16.710
they fail a screen test
and they do what they've to do.

13:16.910 --> 13:18.450
Could any member
of the Corbata Club

13:18.650 --> 13:20.410
not know that he was dead?

13:20.610 --> 13:22.070
From our own Chief of Detectives

13:22.270 --> 13:24.240
to the new
Ambassador to England,

13:24.440 --> 13:26.770
I find it highly unlikely
it didn't come up over cream tea

13:26.970 --> 13:29.990
that a scumbag had caught
a Buick at the front entrance.

13:30.190 --> 13:32.380
Did they ask you
to broom the case?

13:32.580 --> 13:34.770
No one has to ask, my brother.

13:34.970 --> 13:36.420
Can I see the police file?

13:37.680 --> 13:39.160
We don't need it.

13:44.300 --> 13:45.820
Why you looking for this guy?

13:47.520 --> 13:49.660
A lady wanted to find him.

13:49.860 --> 13:51.480
Well, he'll wait
until she comes by.

13:53.090 --> 13:55.530
[suspenseful music]

14:07.970 --> 14:12.160
Dorothy: Go back to Boston, to
that miserable goddamn family.

14:12.360 --> 14:18.210
And then onto England, the court
of Saint fucking James.

14:18.410 --> 14:21.260
You're not the only one
who's done with this.

14:21.460 --> 14:22.520
Just remember one thing.

14:22.720 --> 14:25.000
Oh, please, darling,
not another.

14:25.200 --> 14:27.090
I paid for that horse.

14:27.290 --> 14:28.860
Dorothy: I get to keep him too.

14:32.740 --> 14:34.480
Could you, uh, do mine after?

14:38.830 --> 14:40.270
Are you the new mechanic?

14:40.470 --> 14:42.280
Maybe, what's it paying?

14:42.480 --> 14:44.760
- You've a name?
- Marlowe.

14:44.960 --> 14:46.930
This is hell nor am I out of it.

14:47.130 --> 14:48.670
That was his one good line.

14:48.870 --> 14:50.980
You don't think
he was Shakespeare.

14:51.180 --> 14:52.500
Neither did he.

14:52.700 --> 14:54.240
Joseph: Maybe I am out of it.

14:56.590 --> 14:58.070
Well out of it.

15:03.200 --> 15:05.640
[music continues]

15:19.440 --> 15:21.660
You startled me, Marlowe.

15:21.860 --> 15:24.570
Apologies, seems to be my day
for startling.

15:28.920 --> 15:30.720
Who else did you startle?

15:30.920 --> 15:33.970
Some elegant Mick outside,
who quoted Marlowe.

15:35.490 --> 15:36.770
Are you quotable, Mr. Marlowe?

15:36.970 --> 15:38.330
Christopher Marlowe.

15:38.530 --> 15:42.380
Ah, he played in Doctor Faustus
at the Harvard Rep.

15:42.580 --> 15:43.990
Never lets anyone forget that.

15:44.190 --> 15:46.170
- He?
- Hm.

15:46.370 --> 15:49.910
Joseph O'Reilly,
my mother's financial adviser,

15:50.110 --> 15:52.960
oh, and soon to be
Ambassador to England,

15:53.160 --> 15:55.740
he never lets anyone forget
about that either.

15:55.940 --> 15:58.350
What did he play,
one of the seven deadly sins?

15:58.550 --> 16:00.080
[chuckles]
Please.

16:01.780 --> 16:04.270
Iced tea?

16:04.470 --> 16:05.750
You could have some of mine
if you like.

16:05.950 --> 16:07.840
Marlowe: No, thank you.

16:08.040 --> 16:09.970
I can offer you anything really,

16:10.170 --> 16:11.670
it's like the Arabian Nights
around here.

16:11.870 --> 16:13.050
Richard: Clare!

16:14.060 --> 16:15.320
Clare!

16:19.710 --> 16:21.150
Who the hell is this?

16:22.720 --> 16:25.420
Sorry, I'm, I'm Philip Marlowe.

16:25.620 --> 16:29.470
Hello, Marlowe.
Cavendish.

16:29.670 --> 16:33.340
Clare: Mr. Marlowe calls me
Cavendish, Richard. I like it.

16:33.540 --> 16:34.910
It's your name, darling.

16:35.110 --> 16:36.740
I like it as a first name.

16:36.940 --> 16:38.870
Richard: Glad I'm good
for something, dear.

16:39.070 --> 16:40.570
Have you, um, offered

16:40.770 --> 16:43.700
your very large friend
a proper drink, darling?

16:43.900 --> 16:47.230
She did, and I declined,
thank you.

16:47.430 --> 16:52.020
So, Mr. Marlowe, what kind of
business are you in?

16:52.210 --> 16:54.060
Mr. Marlowe detects things.

16:54.260 --> 16:57.110
Ah, and what are you
detecting here, Marlowe?

16:57.310 --> 17:00.810
My necklace.
I lost it, he found it.

17:01.010 --> 17:03.940
Richard: Of course he did.
I wonder where.

17:04.140 --> 17:06.590
Well, it was a matter of
retracing your wife's steps.

17:08.070 --> 17:10.420
- Marlowe.
- Yes, Mr. Cavendish.

17:10.620 --> 17:11.810
Fuck yourself.

17:13.330 --> 17:15.550
It's a pleasure to meet you too,
Mr. Cavendish.

17:17.340 --> 17:19.380
Clare: Didn't go for it,
that's odd.

17:21.120 --> 17:23.210
He must think there's
something between us...

17:24.650 --> 17:28.260
probably something... sexual.

17:30.310 --> 17:32.790
So tell me about you
and Mr. Peterson

17:32.990 --> 17:35.320
with no embellishments,
please.

17:35.520 --> 17:37.180
[instrumental music]

17:39.490 --> 17:42.800
<i>Clare: I met him at the Corbata</i>
<i>Club for the first time.</i>

17:43.000 --> 17:44.980
Thought he was handsome.

17:45.180 --> 17:50.290
We made love, and then I saw
him again, a few weeks later,

17:50.490 --> 17:53.160
not an assignation,
an accident.

17:53.360 --> 17:57.300
In Tijuana at my favorite bar,
La Quinteria.

17:57.500 --> 17:59.470
<i>I was there with my husband.</i>

17:59.670 --> 18:02.380
<i>We were watching the </i>
<i>procession, Dia de los Muertos.</i>

18:05.600 --> 18:08.040
[man whistling]

18:18.790 --> 18:20.710
<i>Marlowe: What was</i>
<i>he hustling in Mexico?</i>

18:20.910 --> 18:24.270
<i>Clare: I don't know.</i>
<i>Nico has many schemes.</i>

18:26.580 --> 18:28.240
<i>Marlowe: He's in the grave.</i>

18:28.440 --> 18:30.640
Nico Peterson is dead.

18:30.830 --> 18:32.110
He's pretending.

18:33.500 --> 18:35.210
He's pretending very well.

18:35.400 --> 18:37.950
Clare: Oh, I know,
he's dead and buried.

18:38.150 --> 18:42.160
That he got killed in front of
the Corbata Club, supposedly.

18:44.340 --> 18:47.090
Everybody says he was.

18:47.290 --> 18:50.310
But you see, the significant
thing is that

18:50.510 --> 18:53.700
I saw him the other day,
from the street,

18:53.900 --> 18:55.620
not in my mind's eye,

18:55.820 --> 18:58.320
on the street,
not dead at all.

18:58.510 --> 19:00.710
I think we're finished,
Mrs. Cavendish.

19:00.910 --> 19:01.920
No.

19:03.490 --> 19:05.400
I just wanted you to start
at the beginning.

19:06.920 --> 19:08.240
Begin at the beginning,

19:08.440 --> 19:10.680
that's what you're supposed
to do, right?

19:10.870 --> 19:13.500
- Where did you see him?
- Back in Tijuana.

19:13.700 --> 19:17.120
My mother wanted me to view
some Azteca horses,

19:17.320 --> 19:18.670
you know the prancing kind.

19:20.420 --> 19:24.520
I did that,
I do what she says.

19:24.710 --> 19:26.730
<i>So I was in La Quinteria again,</i>

19:26.930 --> 19:29.390
<i>having one of their</i>
<i>divine mojitos</i>

19:29.590 --> 19:31.700
<i>when I saw Nico</i>
<i>driving down the street.</i>

19:31.900 --> 19:33.950
[singing in foreign language]

19:42.520 --> 19:44.710
<i>Clare: He called himself</i>
<i>a collector.</i>

19:44.910 --> 19:48.660
<i>Most of all collected junk,</i>
<i>pretend antiques.</i>

19:52.620 --> 19:56.070
I suppose
they're for the movies...

19:56.270 --> 19:59.410
things that don't exist,
fairy tales.

20:00.760 --> 20:02.030
There's a man in Baja,

20:02.230 --> 20:04.380
who thinks Nico's
actually a producer.

20:04.580 --> 20:05.770
[laughs]

20:05.970 --> 20:07.290
He's been fleeced.

20:09.510 --> 20:11.690
What? What's wrong?

20:11.890 --> 20:13.870
You lied to me, Mrs. Cavendish.

20:14.070 --> 20:16.520
And I sat there and watched you
lie to your husband.

20:16.720 --> 20:18.080
Good afternoon.

20:30.570 --> 20:32.630
Hello, Mr...

20:32.830 --> 20:33.800
Marlowe.

20:34.000 --> 20:35.370
Oh, of course, I knew that.

20:35.570 --> 20:38.020
Richard made a call
when you first came in.

20:38.220 --> 20:40.330
You know what they say
about the old boys' club?

20:40.530 --> 20:41.980
What's that?

20:42.180 --> 20:43.990
There really is one.

20:44.190 --> 20:46.950
And what did he find,
Madame, uh...

20:47.140 --> 20:51.380
Dorothy Quincannon, and
don't pretend you don't know.

20:53.990 --> 20:57.740
Well, let's see,
you had a bad war,

20:57.940 --> 20:59.780
and then in the twenties,
you drank yourself

20:59.980 --> 21:01.480
out of a good job
in the oil business.

21:01.680 --> 21:02.530
Did I?

21:02.730 --> 21:04.790
Got on with the Los Angeles DA

21:04.990 --> 21:07.920
as an investigator, but that
didn't work out too well either,

21:08.120 --> 21:09.920
did it, Mr. Marlowe?

21:10.120 --> 21:12.660
You see, he found all that out
in five minutes.

21:14.220 --> 21:17.670
You're not the only one
who can make enquiries.

21:17.870 --> 21:20.630
You weren't looking for pearls.

21:20.830 --> 21:25.070
No, I throw them before swine,
it's a habit of mine.

21:25.270 --> 21:28.860
Tell me, Mr. Marlowe,
what does my daughter want?

21:29.060 --> 21:32.430
A divorce?
I might even approve.

21:32.630 --> 21:35.300
I'm sorry, I only discuss
business with my employer,

21:35.500 --> 21:38.300
so if you'll excuse me.

21:38.500 --> 21:40.290
<i>- Slan.</i>
<i>- Slan.</i>

22:11.850 --> 22:13.330
[sighs]

22:27.210 --> 22:29.650
[suspenseful music]

22:40.700 --> 22:42.360
Marlowe: Excuse me?

23:02.460 --> 23:04.470
- Hey, Fergus.
- Oh, hello.

23:04.670 --> 23:06.820
Ah, Jesus, here it is.

23:07.020 --> 23:09.350
Not a single lead
on who ran Peterson down.

23:09.550 --> 23:12.260
- We pursued inquiries.
- But how far?

23:12.460 --> 23:15.350
Marlowe, if one wanted
to find an absolute nest

23:15.550 --> 23:17.570
of entitled
and connected tosspots

23:17.770 --> 23:19.360
who feel they can
just drive away

23:19.560 --> 23:21.060
after running over
another drunk's head,

23:21.260 --> 23:23.490
you go to the Corbata Club.

23:23.690 --> 23:26.630
There were no witnesses,
a suspect wasn't possible.

23:26.830 --> 23:28.630
Saturday night, they come and go
at that club like rats

23:28.830 --> 23:30.590
through a hole in a garbage can.

23:30.790 --> 23:32.240
It could have been
any one of a hundred cars

23:32.440 --> 23:34.770
that flattened him, and probably
none of them contained

23:34.960 --> 23:37.070
anybody it'd be wise to arrest.

23:37.270 --> 23:40.770
We're in the real world here.
You understand a real world.

23:40.970 --> 23:42.510
Sometimes justice is blind,

23:42.710 --> 23:45.170
sometimes justice doesn't give
a shit and might be right.

23:45.370 --> 23:48.300
So who's the mystery broad
you're working for? His sister?

23:48.500 --> 23:49.870
Tell me about his sister.

23:50.070 --> 23:51.960
Maybe she identified him,
maybe she didn't.

23:52.160 --> 23:53.740
You tell me about his sister.

23:53.940 --> 23:57.400
I got my own sister, you can
stick his sister up your ass.

23:57.600 --> 23:59.050
I'm working for a person
who thinks

23:59.250 --> 24:02.400
that Nico Peterson
is still alive.

24:02.600 --> 24:06.490
Yeah, that's complicated.
I'm not a complicated man.

24:06.690 --> 24:08.840
My client claims
to have seen him,

24:09.040 --> 24:11.190
which gives you
a murder, my friend.

24:11.390 --> 24:13.100
Yeah, I got plenty, thanks.

24:15.190 --> 24:16.490
Here's your file.

24:19.020 --> 24:21.590
My employer thinks
he didn't die,

24:21.790 --> 24:23.120
that it wasn't him
that got smashed

24:23.320 --> 24:26.250
outside the Corbata Club,
to repeat myself.

24:26.450 --> 24:30.820
It gives me a murder, yeah,
theoretically, maybe.

24:31.020 --> 24:34.130
What's your trouble gents?
Money or women?

24:34.330 --> 24:36.350
Both, with the
complication of thirst.

24:36.550 --> 24:39.530
He's like the rest of us, Pat,
except he can't take a hint.

24:39.730 --> 24:41.270
- What'll you have?
- Whiskey.

24:41.470 --> 24:43.620
Usual.

24:43.820 --> 24:45.010
What's going on these days
Patrick,

24:45.210 --> 24:46.840
you, you married, or happy?

24:47.040 --> 24:48.580
At least my laundry's done.

24:48.780 --> 24:50.010
Pat had a rough
two weeks finding

24:50.210 --> 24:53.150
clean drawers after
he lost his mother.

24:53.350 --> 24:54.450
Fuck yourself.

24:54.650 --> 24:56.280
If I could, I wouldn't
have to listen.

24:56.480 --> 24:58.750
If it was an operation,
I'd sign up.

25:00.360 --> 25:02.890
If he's alive, Joe,
you have a homicide.

25:04.720 --> 25:06.600
Gonna keep saying that?

25:06.800 --> 25:08.470
That's the last thing
you want in homicide,

25:08.670 --> 25:10.080
I realize, homicide.

25:10.280 --> 25:12.690
What, you think
it was a homicide?

25:12.890 --> 25:15.300
I went to the graveyard.
Guess what?

25:15.500 --> 25:17.350
- He was cremated.
- Good guess.

25:17.550 --> 25:20.440
Yeah, even the teeth
were destroyed

25:20.640 --> 25:21.870
and they'd be everywhere.

25:22.070 --> 25:24.400
You ever run over a rat
or a cat, look at it?

25:24.600 --> 25:27.750
If Peterson didn't die, who did?

25:27.950 --> 25:31.930
Look, Marlowe, I know you got
this Sir Lancelot bullshit,

25:32.130 --> 25:33.490
and you live like some monk,

25:33.690 --> 25:36.670
you got no regular self-interest
anyone can count on,

25:36.870 --> 25:39.890
you like getting sapped and
locked up for just not stopping,

25:40.090 --> 25:44.160
and this is an interesting story
you have, if true.

25:44.350 --> 25:47.380
But that stiff, Peterson,
for all intents and purposes,

25:47.580 --> 25:49.640
had Peterson's wallet
in his pocket.

25:49.840 --> 25:51.420
Plus, he was identified
at the scene,

25:51.620 --> 25:53.160
for all intents and purposes.

25:53.360 --> 25:54.470
By who?

25:54.670 --> 25:56.080
The manager of the club,
Floyd Hanson,

25:56.280 --> 25:59.170
and by the Los Angeles
County Coroner, who's a member.

25:59.370 --> 26:02.080
So, it's nobody's business now
but county.

26:03.250 --> 26:04.650
County line runs where?

26:04.850 --> 26:06.390
Bay Canyon Drive.

26:11.430 --> 26:13.400
Right along here?

26:13.600 --> 26:15.220
Oh, Jesus.

26:18.440 --> 26:19.830
Make the call, Joe.

26:21.230 --> 26:22.920
I'll keep you out of it.

26:27.230 --> 26:29.150
[engine revving]

26:33.720 --> 26:37.560
Mr. Hanson says it's most
irregular, Mr. Marlowe,

26:37.760 --> 26:39.250
but he'll see you.

26:39.450 --> 26:42.040
Keep to the left, follow
the signs that say reception.

26:42.240 --> 26:43.520
Oh, thank you.

26:43.720 --> 26:46.030
[suspenseful music]

27:14.280 --> 27:15.930
Floyd: I'm Floyd Hanson
the manager.

27:17.500 --> 27:18.950
What can I do for you,
Mr. Marlowe?

27:19.150 --> 27:21.770
Don't bother turning off
the car.

27:21.970 --> 27:23.860
The gateman tells me
you're a private investigator,

27:24.060 --> 27:25.390
could that be so?

27:25.590 --> 27:28.090
Yes, I used to work
for the DA's office.

27:28.280 --> 27:31.040
- I've heard that.
- I've heard that you've heard.

27:31.240 --> 27:33.530
[engine turns off]

27:33.730 --> 27:36.040
I'm here about an
accident that occurred.

27:38.090 --> 27:40.620
- A serious one?
- Nico Peterson.

27:40.820 --> 27:42.060
Well, that actually
wasn't on the property,

27:42.260 --> 27:43.540
that was more
in the public road.

27:43.740 --> 27:46.020
Oh, I fully appreciate
the distinction,

27:46.220 --> 27:48.630
but sometimes people
get moved off the property

27:48.830 --> 27:51.980
even though their leg is lying
on it a little bit.

27:52.180 --> 27:54.420
There was an interesting case
in Cincinnati.

27:54.620 --> 27:56.200
What was that?

27:56.400 --> 27:59.600
A man was beaten to death,
and then he was put in the road,

27:59.790 --> 28:02.080
and his head was run over
by a tire,

28:02.280 --> 28:04.600
to obliterate the cause of death

28:04.800 --> 28:06.990
and to get him off the property.

28:07.190 --> 28:08.650
Mr. Peterson was run down
on the road,

28:08.850 --> 28:10.610
and the road is not
on the property.

28:10.810 --> 28:12.430
I appreciate that.

28:12.630 --> 28:14.650
Was Peterson a member
of this club?

28:14.850 --> 28:17.440
No, Mr. Peterson
wasn't a member. No.

28:17.640 --> 28:19.570
Marlowe: That's because
you're exclusive I imagine.

28:19.770 --> 28:21.920
Floyd: We are,
but your meaning, sir?

28:22.120 --> 28:24.180
[indistinct chatter]

28:24.380 --> 28:26.100
What would we do without Mexico?

28:26.300 --> 28:29.710
Mexico's the future, we have a
sister club in Baja, California.

28:29.910 --> 28:32.540
- Looks like the past.
- It must be brought along.

28:32.740 --> 28:34.670
Mexico or its inhabitants?

28:34.870 --> 28:36.230
Stick to the point, Mr. Marlowe.

28:37.670 --> 28:39.030
It must have been
a shock for you,

28:39.230 --> 28:41.640
seeing Mr. Peterson
on the road like that.

28:41.840 --> 28:44.810
I was at Chateau Thierry,
old man, Belleau Wood.

28:45.010 --> 28:46.380
I have seen men in more disarray

28:46.580 --> 28:48.290
than that in which
Mr. Peterson was discovered.

28:49.940 --> 28:51.600
Once, after an artillery strike,

28:51.800 --> 28:54.390
I found a friend's tooth
in my whiskey glass.

28:54.590 --> 28:55.900
I drank the whiskey.

28:57.030 --> 28:58.830
You're a terrible man.

28:59.030 --> 29:01.700
He was dead,
and I needed the whiskey.

29:01.900 --> 29:04.050
You're my age,
perhaps you were there,

29:04.250 --> 29:07.140
perhaps you know how it was,
and therefore is.

29:07.340 --> 29:10.450
Royal Irish Rifles.
The Somme.

29:10.650 --> 29:12.750
For the rest of time,
we see the dead.

29:14.970 --> 29:16.720
Let's take a stroll,
Mr. Marlowe.

29:16.920 --> 29:18.940
We're alive,
when others are not,

29:19.130 --> 29:20.670
and it's a pleasant morning.

29:23.150 --> 29:25.500
[suspenseful music]

29:27.800 --> 29:28.990
Marlowe: I see
you've made inequity

29:29.190 --> 29:30.510
pretty much your profession.

29:30.710 --> 29:33.510
The Club is exclusive.
The rich like to play.

29:33.710 --> 29:36.300
The polo grounds are over there.

29:36.500 --> 29:40.910
So whose guest was Mr. Peterson
the night he was killed?

29:41.110 --> 29:43.310
Who's your employer Mr. Marlowe?

29:43.510 --> 29:46.270
We're at an impasse,
Mr. Hanson. Who's yours?

29:46.470 --> 29:47.880
I don't know
what you want me to tell you,

29:48.080 --> 29:50.230
the police were thorough,
aren't they always,

29:50.430 --> 29:53.060
isn't that what they do,
be thorough?

29:53.260 --> 29:56.710
I rarely blame a policeman
unless he's really bad.

29:56.910 --> 29:59.410
There's generally someone
he's afraid of.

29:59.610 --> 30:03.020
And who in this instance would
any policeman be afraid of?

30:03.220 --> 30:05.070
Well, if the hit and run driver

30:05.270 --> 30:09.030
were a very substantial
or a connected person,

30:09.230 --> 30:11.380
a policeman might be afraid
of the Club in general.

30:11.580 --> 30:13.160
I mean, I am.

30:13.360 --> 30:16.120
What would it take for you
not to be afraid? What can I do?

30:16.320 --> 30:19.560
Now, listen, Mr. Hanson,
I intend to ask questions.

30:19.760 --> 30:21.260
Then ask your damn questions.

30:21.460 --> 30:23.260
Now this was a hit and run,

30:23.460 --> 30:25.180
and given the road,
it was probably a member,

30:25.370 --> 30:29.050
and perhaps the driver didn't
even know he'd struck anything.

30:29.250 --> 30:31.790
Everybody in this country has
been drunk since its inception.

30:31.990 --> 30:34.570
I don't think I've ever even
seen a sober driver.

30:36.350 --> 30:37.700
Shall we have some tea?

30:40.360 --> 30:42.060
<i>Marlowe: Is there much</i>
<i>gambling here, Mr. Hanson?</i>

30:42.260 --> 30:43.980
You're on very dangerous ground.

30:44.180 --> 30:45.460
There are cards that are played.

30:45.660 --> 30:46.980
Debts accumulated.

30:47.180 --> 30:49.500
There are card rooms,
they're private.

30:49.700 --> 30:50.810
Bedrooms?

30:51.010 --> 30:52.940
We have guest accommodations.

30:53.140 --> 30:55.670
Do studio men and the producers
have meetings here?

30:56.630 --> 30:58.640
Why am I talking to you?

30:58.840 --> 31:00.990
Because you don't know
who hired me.

31:01.190 --> 31:02.600
Well, name the thing
that most intrigues you,

31:02.800 --> 31:05.650
perhaps we could
conclude our chat.

31:05.850 --> 31:07.740
There is the possibility
that the dead man

31:07.940 --> 31:10.610
was not Nico Peterson.

31:10.810 --> 31:13.880
His sister was shown his corpse
the next day at the morgue

31:14.080 --> 31:15.440
and expressed no doubts.

31:15.640 --> 31:17.000
Where could I find his sister?

31:19.610 --> 31:21.140
Ask the police.

31:21.340 --> 31:23.440
[suspenseful music]

31:33.760 --> 31:37.420
Why do you raise the possibility
that Peterson is alive,

31:37.620 --> 31:39.470
when I so clearly saw him dead?

31:39.670 --> 31:42.690
Someone may have seen him
recently in the street.

31:42.890 --> 31:45.860
And where was this,
uh, supposedly?

31:46.060 --> 31:47.120
I can't tell you.

31:48.470 --> 31:50.130
Goodbye, Mr. Marlowe.

31:50.330 --> 31:53.470
I'm sorry that it was ultimately
uninteresting to talk to you.

31:56.000 --> 31:57.620
Ah, but I do like this thing
that you have

31:57.810 --> 32:00.300
about not being afraid,
when you should be.

32:03.610 --> 32:05.270
I'll see myself out.

32:14.450 --> 32:16.890
[instrumental music]

32:20.980 --> 32:23.770
♪ Sometimes it seems

32:23.970 --> 32:26.560
♪ A part of the sin...

32:26.760 --> 32:28.820
Man 2: You're the most beautiful
woman in town.

32:29.020 --> 32:30.340
A star.

32:30.540 --> 32:32.120
[woman giggles]

32:34.380 --> 32:37.300
♪ Sometimes it seems

32:38.600 --> 32:42.140
My, my!
You're not a regular.

32:42.340 --> 32:44.490
Well, not yet anyway.

32:44.690 --> 32:46.530
They do like to keep it
exclusive.

32:46.730 --> 32:48.350
Yeah, it seems that way.

32:50.090 --> 32:52.840
Try me at the Cabana,
Venice Beach.

32:54.050 --> 32:55.590
Excuse me?

32:55.790 --> 32:57.330
Try me at the Cabana,
Venice Beach.

32:57.530 --> 32:59.070
Ask for Lynn, Lynn Peterson.

32:59.270 --> 33:02.250
- You're Nico's sister.
- Sir?

33:02.440 --> 33:03.850
Gentlemen.

33:06.070 --> 33:08.500
<i>[Jade Vincent singing</i>
<i>"Impossible"]</i>

33:13.900 --> 33:16.160
[engine revving]

33:36.360 --> 33:39.460
♪ Learn to play

33:39.660 --> 33:42.550
<i>Marlowe: Lynn, I'm not sure</i>
<i>if it's an N, or an E.</i>

33:42.750 --> 33:44.940
Madam Cabana: With an X
if she works here.

33:45.140 --> 33:46.680
There you go.

33:46.880 --> 33:48.810
Robe's in the cabinet,
and no monkey business.

33:49.010 --> 33:50.420
I'll try not to.

33:50.620 --> 33:53.420
♪ Kindly fade away

33:55.160 --> 33:57.640
<i>[Jade Vincent singing</i>
<i>"Impossible"]</i>

34:08.260 --> 34:09.960
Marlowe: Thank you.
Woman 1: You're welcome.

34:11.440 --> 34:13.350
Here he is.

34:17.140 --> 34:19.890
Mr. Hanson sends his apologies,

34:20.090 --> 34:21.800
Lynn Peterson's been detained.

34:22.000 --> 34:26.370
Oh, I'm, uh,
I'm sorry to hear that.

34:26.570 --> 34:28.500
Is that, uh, Lynn with an X?

34:30.240 --> 34:31.810
[grunts]

34:32.010 --> 34:34.760
[groaning]

34:39.460 --> 34:40.810
Ah, fuck it.

34:42.030 --> 34:43.380
[groans]

34:44.510 --> 34:46.210
I'm getting too old for this.

34:59.830 --> 35:02.190
<i>Hilda: Are you keeping</i>
<i>evil company?</i>

35:02.390 --> 35:03.930
<i>Marlowe: More often than not.</i>

35:04.130 --> 35:05.540
<i>Hilda: Well, then,</i>
<i>you'd better be a good boy,</i>

35:05.740 --> 35:07.850
because you're going to meet
Dorothy Quincannon

35:08.050 --> 35:10.030
at The Garden of Allah Hotel
at 3:00.

35:10.220 --> 35:13.280
That's in 20 minutes.
Dorothy Quincannon.

35:17.760 --> 35:20.080
Did you come
for the film stars, Hilda?

35:20.280 --> 35:22.300
I came to bloody be one.

35:22.500 --> 35:23.430
Huh.

35:23.630 --> 35:25.900
[instrumental music]

35:33.870 --> 35:35.750
Dorothy: First of all,
you have to boil the water,

35:35.950 --> 35:37.440
now is that water boiled?

35:37.640 --> 35:39.400
- Waiter: Yes, ma'am.
- And then scald the teapot.

35:39.600 --> 35:41.530
- Give it a good scalding.
- Alright.

35:41.730 --> 35:45.410
Put in one teaspoon per cup,
then one for the pot

35:45.610 --> 35:48.270
and then leave it to draw
for three minutes.

35:50.060 --> 35:52.240
Think of a soft boiled egg,
darling,

35:52.440 --> 35:54.980
three minutes,
no more, no less

35:55.180 --> 35:57.330
and then you're ready to pour,
have you got that?

35:57.530 --> 35:59.380
Waiter: Y-- yes, ma'am.

35:59.580 --> 36:01.160
When you make tea, make tea.

36:01.360 --> 36:03.990
When you make water, make water.

36:04.190 --> 36:05.520
Waiter: Water.

36:05.710 --> 36:07.130
I-- I don't think he got it.

36:07.330 --> 36:09.820
[laughs]
Did you?

36:10.020 --> 36:11.960
You lifted it from Joyce, ma'am.

36:12.160 --> 36:14.960
Uh-ho, and he lifted it
from somewhere else,

36:15.160 --> 36:16.400
shitty little man that he is.

36:16.600 --> 36:18.140
Never a day's work in his life.

36:18.340 --> 36:20.230
Yeah, apart from the books.

36:20.430 --> 36:22.530
Terrible little syphilitic.

36:22.730 --> 36:24.360
Tricked an American,

36:24.560 --> 36:26.540
sometimes that's all
you have to do.

36:26.740 --> 36:27.930
Is that what you did?

36:28.130 --> 36:30.630
I've tricked any number
of Americans,

36:30.830 --> 36:34.720
including playing
pagan princesses,

36:34.920 --> 36:37.980
Elizabeth of England,
ruined widows

36:38.180 --> 36:42.290
and any number of flash-eyed
barefoot peasant girls.

36:42.490 --> 36:44.160
There's nothing to it,
all you need

36:44.360 --> 36:46.770
are regular features
and the ability to read.

36:46.970 --> 36:49.200
Oh, I very much doubt that.

36:53.290 --> 36:55.000
I spoke with my daughter.

36:55.200 --> 36:58.130
Surprisingly, she's not at all
interested in getting a divorce.

36:58.330 --> 37:00.440
- She loves her husband.
- No.

37:00.640 --> 37:03.790
[laughs]
But the arrangement suits her.

37:03.990 --> 37:06.970
Alcohol, waitresses
and her money.

37:07.170 --> 37:08.350
My money.

37:10.050 --> 37:14.150
She hired you to find
another swine, didn't she?

37:14.350 --> 37:17.540
Nico Peterson,
who doesn't want to be found.

37:17.740 --> 37:20.590
You learned
all of this from her, yeah?

37:20.790 --> 37:24.890
Ah! I want that tea strong
enough to trot a mouse on.

37:27.330 --> 37:31.730
Fine, done, you can go now,
I will be mother.

37:31.930 --> 37:33.260
Waiter: Thank you, ma'am.

37:33.450 --> 37:34.810
[laughs]

37:36.680 --> 37:40.650
I have also had the pleasure
of Mr. Peterson's company,

37:40.850 --> 37:43.220
he was proposing
certain investments.

37:43.420 --> 37:45.480
Marlowe: In the equitation
business, I presume.

37:45.680 --> 37:48.570
Whatever business,
I wasn't interested.

37:48.770 --> 37:51.490
But my daughter cannot help

37:51.690 --> 37:54.410
but want what
she presumes I have.

37:54.610 --> 37:56.830
And you had Mr. Peterson?

37:58.360 --> 38:00.850
That was a presumption,
Mr. Marlowe.

38:01.050 --> 38:02.630
Marlowe: An understandable one.

38:02.830 --> 38:04.900
Dorothy: I'm sure my daughter's
paying you handsomely.

38:05.090 --> 38:07.810
I can't talk to you
about your daughter's business.

38:08.010 --> 38:12.860
What business do you think there
is in my family that isn't mine?

38:13.060 --> 38:17.080
If she thought I wanted you,
she'd have you too.

38:17.280 --> 38:21.260
Mm. Perhaps she already has.

38:21.460 --> 38:23.700
I can only say it again,
I'm not in a position

38:23.900 --> 38:26.090
to discuss your daughter's
business with you.

38:26.290 --> 38:30.790
You're a proud stubborn man,
Mr. Marlowe.

38:30.990 --> 38:33.230
I'm just an ordinary Joe

38:33.430 --> 38:36.050
trying to earn a buck
and stay out of jail.

38:40.570 --> 38:44.020
Clare's father drove his car
off a cliff in La Jolla

38:44.220 --> 38:46.720
before she was even born.

38:46.920 --> 38:51.290
He was in the oil business,
very successful,

38:51.490 --> 38:55.640
but he couldn't hide
from the black dog.

38:55.840 --> 38:59.560
It's the one thing that
frightens me, Mr. Marlowe.

38:59.760 --> 39:02.950
That hound,
it runs in families.

39:03.150 --> 39:04.960
You're afraid she's unstable?

39:05.150 --> 39:06.640
Oh, I know she is.

39:08.380 --> 39:10.660
So be careful, Mr. Marlowe,

39:10.860 --> 39:14.700
she has this burning need
for a father figure.

39:14.900 --> 39:17.270
You see, I had to pretend

39:17.470 --> 39:20.320
that she was my niece
all those years.

39:20.520 --> 39:23.790
My advisers thought that,
uh, a daughter...

39:25.270 --> 39:26.500
would age me.

39:26.700 --> 39:28.200
Marlowe: What advisers?

39:28.400 --> 39:32.500
You've met the soon to be
Ambassador to England.

39:32.700 --> 39:34.110
Mr. O'Reilly.

39:34.310 --> 39:36.770
Dorothy: And maybe
he advised me wrongly,

39:36.970 --> 39:40.470
but I had to listen
all those years.

39:40.670 --> 39:42.300
He even bought a studio,

39:42.500 --> 39:44.170
said it was to
advance my career,

39:44.370 --> 39:48.130
but it did no harm
to his bank balance.

39:48.330 --> 39:51.570
So, my daughter
had to be my niece...

39:51.770 --> 39:55.010
until at last even
I had to face the fact.

39:55.200 --> 39:57.140
The fact?

39:57.340 --> 40:02.140
That my game was up,
it had been for some time.

40:02.340 --> 40:06.530
No more barefoot colleens,
no more Ruritanian queens.

40:08.660 --> 40:12.330
I have more money
than the Queen of Sheba,

40:12.530 --> 40:15.370
and I'm a very, very,
very happy has-been.

40:15.570 --> 40:18.160
You mean a celluloid legend,
surely.

40:18.360 --> 40:20.730
The key to Hollywood,
Mr. Marlowe,

40:20.930 --> 40:23.510
is knowing
when your game is up.

40:23.710 --> 40:27.950
Take the money and run,
or stay, if you want.

40:28.150 --> 40:29.860
But at least take the money.

40:32.210 --> 40:36.350
I had another investigator
on Mr. Peterson's case,

40:36.550 --> 40:38.660
a shamus, called Seamus,
if you can believe.

40:38.860 --> 40:40.530
What did he find?

40:40.730 --> 40:43.580
Dorothy: That besides being prop
master at Pacific Pictures,

40:43.780 --> 40:47.230
Nico was also a wannabe agent
with the client of one,

40:47.430 --> 40:50.230
Miss Amanda Toxteth.

40:50.430 --> 40:54.460
So you see, Mr. Marlowe,
my daughter wasn't the only one

40:54.660 --> 40:57.420
spreading her legs for him.

40:57.620 --> 41:00.770
So, if you find Mr. Peterson,
come to me before--

41:00.970 --> 41:04.380
Where would I find
Miss Toxteth?

41:04.580 --> 41:08.470
Don't know, some god-awful
B picture I suppose.

41:08.670 --> 41:12.210
- Ma'am.
- Wait. How dare you?

41:12.410 --> 41:15.900
I'm a little confused,
I've already been paid.

41:17.250 --> 41:19.170
[suspenseful music]

41:27.390 --> 41:29.130
[gunfire]

41:31.270 --> 41:33.890
Cut! Cut! Cut!

41:34.090 --> 41:35.760
I need to see the face,
the face,

41:35.960 --> 41:37.150
I need to see the face.

41:37.350 --> 41:40.500
Ama-- Amanda, uh,
camera's over there,

41:40.700 --> 41:42.030
I need you to look
at the camera.

41:42.220 --> 41:44.720
Car rolls up,
you look at the cameras, okay?

41:44.920 --> 41:46.550
Thank you. Lunch.

41:46.750 --> 41:48.340
I can take this off, right?

41:48.540 --> 41:51.210
Man 3: Yes. After lunch.

41:51.410 --> 41:53.600
Believe me, I look better
without the war paint.

41:53.800 --> 41:56.520
Marlowe: Thanks for seeing me,
Miss Toxteth.

41:56.720 --> 41:59.350
Call me Mandy.
You're a detective?

41:59.550 --> 42:01.440
I'm more harmless than I look.

42:01.640 --> 42:04.260
That must be exciting,
being a detective.

42:04.460 --> 42:05.880
I can hardly contain myself.

42:06.070 --> 42:08.700
Oh, well, don't contain yourself
on my account.

42:08.900 --> 42:11.880
Nico Peterson
was your agent, yes?

42:12.080 --> 42:16.100
Well, he got me some work...

42:16.300 --> 42:18.710
"Riders of the Red Dawn,"
did you see it?

42:18.910 --> 42:24.070
- Mm, not yet, no.
- Well, it's gone now.

42:24.270 --> 42:28.070
Joel McCrea was supposed to be
in it, but something happened.

42:28.270 --> 42:30.600
I play the rancher's wife,
who makes eyes at an Indian,

42:30.800 --> 42:32.380
and the Indian gets hanged.

42:32.580 --> 42:34.110
I'll catch it
when it comes round again.

42:35.770 --> 42:39.210
Acting seems to be going well,
Miss Toxteth.

42:39.410 --> 42:40.950
You're sweet.

42:41.150 --> 42:44.700
Actually, my mother says
I should fuck more producers.

42:44.900 --> 42:46.130
What do you think?

42:46.330 --> 42:49.780
I think your mother
is gravely mistaken.

42:51.780 --> 42:54.880
What can you tell me
about Nico Peterson?

42:55.080 --> 42:57.010
How deeply should my account
be detailed?

42:57.210 --> 42:59.010
Marlowe: Well, when did you
last see him?

43:00.530 --> 43:03.150
I guess a week before he died.

43:03.350 --> 43:05.500
He was trying to get back
into my good graces.

43:05.700 --> 43:09.810
- He was a womanizer, yes?
- That's a tricky question.

43:10.010 --> 43:12.680
Nico liked the conquest,
not the women.

43:12.880 --> 43:15.510
He'd hardly touch you
after he'd had you.

43:15.710 --> 43:17.470
That's a particular kind of man.

43:17.670 --> 43:20.040
Some girls say
handsome men are cold,

43:20.240 --> 43:21.730
that's normally just what
you say to ugly men

43:21.930 --> 43:25.950
to make them feel better,
but... Nico was cold.

43:27.820 --> 43:29.830
Nico had girlfriends,
but he didn't have

43:30.030 --> 43:32.000
girls who were friends.

43:32.200 --> 43:34.700
Do you know any of his
other girlfriends?

43:34.900 --> 43:37.530
Amanda: Clare Quincannon
supposedly fell for him.

43:37.730 --> 43:40.580
The blonde with
the terrible mother.

43:40.780 --> 43:44.970
And the mother's story,
kept by the Ambassador.

43:45.170 --> 43:47.590
He even bought this
studio for her.

43:47.790 --> 43:50.850
I hear it's pure slavery.

43:51.050 --> 43:53.850
Did Nico have anything
to do with Mexico,

43:54.050 --> 43:56.250
business out of Mexico?

43:56.450 --> 43:59.080
There's only one
business out of Mexico,

43:59.270 --> 44:01.160
don't be a sweet chump.

44:01.360 --> 44:04.380
When he had money that was why,
and probably the only reason

44:04.580 --> 44:08.170
anybody would look for him,
owed money or a fix.

44:08.370 --> 44:10.640
[suspenseful music]

44:18.220 --> 44:20.270
What did he drive, Mister?

44:20.470 --> 44:22.530
- Who?
- Nico Peterson.

44:22.730 --> 44:25.010
Well, whatever he drove,
he ain't parking it here.

44:33.620 --> 44:36.020
[dogs barking in distance]

44:53.820 --> 44:55.380
[glass shatters]

44:58.780 --> 45:00.690
[instrumental music]

45:28.810 --> 45:31.720
[music continues]

45:50.740 --> 45:51.970
You again?

45:52.170 --> 45:53.890
It's alright,
I'm a friend of Nico's.

45:54.090 --> 45:56.850
- Philip Marlowe.
- You're much too persistent.

45:57.040 --> 45:59.410
- I'm trying to find Nico.
- He's dead.

45:59.610 --> 46:03.630
Wait a minute.
Are you so sure of that?

46:03.830 --> 46:06.510
I've been hired to look into
your brother's disappearance.

46:06.710 --> 46:09.210
He hasn't disappeared,
he's in a jar on a marble shelf.

46:09.400 --> 46:10.990
I had to buy it myself.

46:11.190 --> 46:13.380
You saw it, too,
should have known.

46:13.580 --> 46:16.170
What if I told you
he might be alive?

46:16.370 --> 46:19.080
I don't believe in
fairy tales, mister.

46:19.280 --> 46:23.310
I saw his body on
the gurney at the place.

46:23.510 --> 46:25.740
So it wasn't at
the club on the roadway.

46:25.940 --> 46:28.530
I did everything I had to.

46:28.730 --> 46:30.230
It couldn't have been
easy seeing him.

46:30.430 --> 46:33.580
Wasn't much fun. And what's
Floyd got against you?

46:33.780 --> 46:36.190
Why I wanted to meet,
and if you're afraid of him

46:36.390 --> 46:37.670
or anything, we have to talk.

46:37.870 --> 46:39.530
I'm not afraid of anything.

46:41.880 --> 46:44.020
- What's in the book?
- Words.

46:44.220 --> 46:45.550
No dope?

46:45.750 --> 46:48.550
Just words,
it's a book about words.

46:48.750 --> 46:52.470
- Nico was good with words.
- You say you saw his body?

46:52.670 --> 46:56.240
Yeah. And then the cop tried
to make me in the hallway.

46:58.030 --> 47:00.820
Probably has a daughter my age.

47:01.020 --> 47:03.610
It's funny, whatever you do,

47:03.810 --> 47:05.610
there is always someone
trying to make ya.

47:05.810 --> 47:07.130
Mm-hmm.

47:07.330 --> 47:11.620
You know what, fuck Floyd,
fuck cops and fuck you.

47:11.810 --> 47:15.140
I know the lady,
she's the punk's sister,

47:15.340 --> 47:17.750
but who are you?

47:17.950 --> 47:19.750
You are a big one.

47:19.950 --> 47:21.800
I'm thinking of
renting the place.

47:22.000 --> 47:23.620
[man laughs]

47:27.490 --> 47:28.760
<i>Donde esta</i>Serena?

47:28.960 --> 47:30.240
Marlowe: Who's Serena?

47:30.440 --> 47:33.370
If you know my brother,
he probably dumped her.

47:36.110 --> 47:38.690
[grunting]

47:38.890 --> 47:40.780
[speaking in foreign language]

47:40.970 --> 47:42.590
[intense music]

47:43.900 --> 47:46.820
[speaking in foreign language]

47:57.650 --> 47:59.180
[speaking in foreign language]

48:02.960 --> 48:05.060
Where's Serena?

48:05.260 --> 48:06.710
- Who's Serena?
- My brother is dead...

48:06.910 --> 48:07.760
Who's Serena?

48:07.960 --> 48:08.930
You take us to her

48:09.130 --> 48:10.370
or you'll see what happens.

48:10.570 --> 48:12.200
[gunshot]

48:12.400 --> 48:13.900
[yelling in foreign language]

48:14.090 --> 48:16.020
[crying]

48:17.850 --> 48:20.110
[speaking in foreign language]

48:25.810 --> 48:26.990
Please.

48:32.950 --> 48:35.560
Cedric: Well, well,
what have we got here?

48:43.000 --> 48:46.880
[chuckles] Boss wants a word.

48:47.080 --> 48:51.310
- And who might you be big guy?
- Cedric, big guy.

48:52.580 --> 48:54.850
Marlowe: Your boss's name?

48:55.050 --> 48:59.160
Oh, he's a little guy,
Lou Hendricks.

48:59.360 --> 49:00.450
Well, well...

49:01.800 --> 49:02.890
Get up.

49:03.720 --> 49:05.330
[groans]

49:08.200 --> 49:11.470
♪ Down the ol'’ big sea wave ♪

49:13.250 --> 49:17.520
♪ I found a new baby

49:17.720 --> 49:19.700
♪ A little baby ♪

49:19.900 --> 49:21.740
[man scatting]

49:32.180 --> 49:34.710
The Lou Hendricks.

49:34.910 --> 49:37.540
Finally, I need
no introduction.

49:37.740 --> 49:41.550
I'm a generic name, Cedric,
an eponymous trademark.

49:41.750 --> 49:43.720
You're a criminal.

49:43.920 --> 49:46.290
Businessman and philanthropist.

49:46.490 --> 49:49.290
I could use a few bucks,
take me away from all this.

49:49.490 --> 49:51.340
I was hoping you could use
a few bucks, Mr. Marlowe,

49:51.540 --> 49:54.170
but alas,
it will be transactional,

49:54.370 --> 49:56.650
not philanthropic.

49:56.850 --> 49:58.780
Well, what was
the words you wanted?

49:58.980 --> 50:01.340
I can only hope
it is not a past participle.

50:03.080 --> 50:05.530
Where's home, Mr. Marlowe?

50:05.730 --> 50:07.970
Where the heart is,
but you know that.

50:08.170 --> 50:12.400
No, I mean your actual,
quotidian home.

50:12.600 --> 50:16.370
26, Maple Boulevard.

50:16.560 --> 50:19.450
Let's take Mr. Marlowe to
his quotidian home, Cedric.

50:21.270 --> 50:25.980
<i>Lou: The Elements of Style</i>
<i>by William Strunk Jr.</i>

50:26.180 --> 50:29.510
A participle phrase at
the beginning of a sentence

50:29.710 --> 50:33.820
must refer to
the grammatical subject.

50:34.020 --> 50:37.820
Walking slowly down the road,
he saw a woman

50:38.020 --> 50:40.030
accompanied by two children.

50:42.080 --> 50:44.650
If you give any trouble...

50:44.850 --> 50:47.740
he will drop you
like a bad grammatical habit.

50:47.940 --> 50:49.690
[engine revving]

50:50.910 --> 50:53.310
[instrumental music]

51:03.750 --> 51:08.070
Lou: Do you need to dress that?
Cedric, your do-rag.

51:08.270 --> 51:10.850
You mean my pocket square,
Mr. Hendricks?

51:11.050 --> 51:13.680
Some days, Cedric, I wish
I'd left you where I found you.

51:13.880 --> 51:16.720
- Give me the goddam thing.
- Thank you.

51:19.980 --> 51:23.390
I hear, Mr. Marlowe,
and from various connections,

51:23.590 --> 51:25.960
that you are
looking for someone.

51:26.160 --> 51:30.080
- We're all looking for someone.
- Oh, that's very sad.

51:31.820 --> 51:34.440
Tell me who I'm looking for.

51:34.640 --> 51:37.190
Let me guess,
two Mexes who are looking

51:37.380 --> 51:38.930
for a broad named Serena.

51:39.130 --> 51:44.630
Serena, a femme of the most
delicate shape imaginable,

51:44.830 --> 51:48.760
last seen in the arms of
one Nico Peterson.

51:48.960 --> 51:52.200
- Does that name ring a bell?
- A tinkle.

51:52.400 --> 51:54.070
I don't need you
to hear a tinkle,

51:54.270 --> 51:56.380
I need you to hear
a sonorous bell

51:56.580 --> 51:58.680
with a hunchback
swinging from it,

51:58.880 --> 52:04.600
gong-a-dong-a-dong,
not a tinkle, Mr. Marlowe.

52:04.800 --> 52:06.810
Who was chasing
Peterson's sister?

52:08.820 --> 52:10.570
Two beaners, I hear.

52:10.770 --> 52:14.920
Maladroits from sunnier climes,
the land of banana

52:15.120 --> 52:17.570
and tarantula, who were also,
quite separately,

52:17.770 --> 52:19.920
and I should like you
to notice that,

52:20.120 --> 52:21.710
looking for her brother.

52:21.910 --> 52:26.280
I would very much appreciate
a word with our friend Nico,

52:26.480 --> 52:30.060
if you find him
and I will pay you.

52:30.260 --> 52:31.980
Tell me what Nico
was involved in

52:32.180 --> 52:35.680
and why he faked
his death and ran.

52:35.880 --> 52:40.150
Nico, in the end,
had to avoid everybody, I think.

52:42.020 --> 52:44.950
But I will tell you that
he used to run errands for me,

52:45.150 --> 52:47.340
down in the land
of the sombrero,

52:47.540 --> 52:49.950
the serape and the mule.

52:50.150 --> 52:52.740
His Spanish was good,
he was dark

52:52.940 --> 52:55.650
in a Latin lover kind of way.

52:55.850 --> 52:57.480
He was useful in Mexico.

52:57.680 --> 53:02.490
Is it bananas or tarantulas
you import, Mr. Hendricks?

53:02.690 --> 53:04.400
Tarantulas.

53:04.600 --> 53:07.800
I'm entirely
composed of tarantulas.

53:08.000 --> 53:12.280
- And me afraid of spiders.
- Nico worked for me.

53:12.480 --> 53:14.630
He would bring me items
so hard to come by up here

53:14.830 --> 53:16.680
where the laws are so strict.

53:16.880 --> 53:18.720
At the time of
his supposed death,

53:18.920 --> 53:22.860
he was in possession
of some of those items.

53:23.060 --> 53:25.120
And these items are?

53:25.320 --> 53:26.950
There are items and items

53:27.150 --> 53:30.650
and one item that
related to the said items.

53:30.850 --> 53:32.600
Why don't we take a ride
to the Corbata Club?

53:32.800 --> 53:34.560
Maybe he stashed
the items there.

53:34.760 --> 53:38.390
Mr. Marlowe, people will talk.

53:38.590 --> 53:41.610
When I go,
I go into the back entrance.

53:41.810 --> 53:43.350
Please leave that remark alone.

53:43.550 --> 53:47.790
- Wouldn't touch it.
- I grease the Corbata.

53:47.990 --> 53:50.010
Lou: Beneath this
fine Charvet shirt

53:50.210 --> 53:52.760
there is nothing but grease.

53:52.950 --> 53:56.150
Peterson would've needed help,
he would've needed a body.

53:56.350 --> 53:58.150
It has conspiracy
written all over it,

53:58.350 --> 54:01.370
I don't think Nico went
to a graveyard with a shovel

54:01.570 --> 54:05.550
and a lamp looking for a stiff
to fit his tuxedo, do you?

54:05.750 --> 54:07.990
The club was in
on the conspiracy,

54:08.190 --> 54:10.340
but what's the club's interest?

54:10.540 --> 54:11.980
Ask your client.

54:13.510 --> 54:15.870
I think you'll keep
looking for Peterson,

54:16.060 --> 54:19.380
client or not,
because you can't stop.

54:22.560 --> 54:24.780
But I'll pay you a thousand
just to sweeten the pot.

54:26.300 --> 54:29.360
No. Cedric, uh,
next street on the right.

54:29.560 --> 54:31.050
Pull over, please.

54:33.530 --> 54:36.840
It would be wise to
reconsider, Mr. Marlowe.

54:37.040 --> 54:39.880
[grim music]

54:41.800 --> 54:44.010
Marlowe:
Stop anywhere here, Cedric.

54:50.150 --> 54:53.160
26, Maple Boulevard,

54:53.360 --> 54:55.560
and I am not so smart
as they think I am.

54:55.760 --> 54:59.130
- You're welcome to come inside.
- They give you back your badge?

54:59.330 --> 55:02.430
No, I'm here to report
a kidnapping.

55:02.630 --> 55:06.700
If you find him, I will know,
and then I'll come get him.

55:06.900 --> 55:10.690
And when that happens,
don't try to stand in the way.

55:14.610 --> 55:16.270
Thanks, Cedric.

55:16.470 --> 55:18.490
<i>Joe: So two Mexes came out</i>
<i>of nowhere and kidnapped</i>

55:18.690 --> 55:19.890
<i>this broad, is that what</i>
<i>you're telling me?</i>

55:20.090 --> 55:22.280
That's what I'm telling
you, that and that

55:22.480 --> 55:25.110
she turns tricks
at the Corbata Club

55:25.310 --> 55:29.330
and identified as her brother a
stiff who wasn't Nico Peterson.

55:29.530 --> 55:32.680
Yeah, there are certain things
I'm just not gonna hear.

55:32.880 --> 55:34.160
They were looking
for another broad,

55:34.360 --> 55:36.900
someone they called Serena.

55:37.100 --> 55:38.380
I'm not here.

55:38.580 --> 55:40.600
[sighs]
His sister was kidnapped.

55:40.800 --> 55:43.300
You don't put it in the system,
I'll go and make a report.

55:43.500 --> 55:46.090
I'll go on the record,
I'll spill that Peterson

55:46.290 --> 55:48.780
wasn't Peterson, and that's
not news, that's a feature.

55:48.980 --> 55:52.270
I can never remember which
newspaper hates the mayor most.

55:52.470 --> 55:55.090
This will all go okay if you
don't manipulate me, okay?

55:55.290 --> 55:57.180
What we do,
we get you out of here,

55:57.380 --> 55:59.320
I take a call from
an anonymous citizen

55:59.520 --> 56:01.320
who saw her put in the car.

56:01.520 --> 56:04.760
And you, play nice, or I'll put
you at the scene as a suspect.

56:04.960 --> 56:05.980
It ain't what happened,
it's what I type.

56:06.170 --> 56:07.720
Deal.

56:07.920 --> 56:10.020
I'll give your pal Bernie
Ohls the dope off the record.

56:10.220 --> 56:12.200
Sheriff's detectives,
I can start everybody looking

56:12.400 --> 56:13.940
for her and they'll look hard.

56:14.140 --> 56:15.770
Is this good enough for you?

56:15.970 --> 56:18.760
- They took my .38.
- Yeah.

56:22.500 --> 56:24.990
There's your .38, if someone
gets killed with your .38,

56:25.190 --> 56:27.820
you still have a .38.

56:28.020 --> 56:30.380
If they ever make us record
serial numbers, it'll be fucked.

56:32.300 --> 56:34.080
[knocking]

56:36.080 --> 56:37.260
Bernie: Marlowe?

56:39.650 --> 56:43.140
- Detective Bernie Ohls.
- Wait in the car, Arthur.

56:43.340 --> 56:46.310
- Get us a drink, Marlowe.
- Scotch on the rocks.

56:49.970 --> 56:52.750
- She's being looked for?
- City, Sheriffs, everybody.

56:53.880 --> 56:55.320
Not a peep out of the brass.

56:57.710 --> 57:00.380
Once a bulletin goes out
nobody can kill her,

57:00.580 --> 57:03.510
all car alert
for Lynn Peterson.

57:03.710 --> 57:07.690
Mexicans driving some
sort of Tijuana spray job.

57:07.890 --> 57:10.080
She'll get no different
than anybody else.

57:10.280 --> 57:12.730
Just really look for her,
I lost her.

57:15.210 --> 57:18.220
When you're getting to be
an old timer,

57:18.420 --> 57:20.350
it's okay to get out alive.

57:20.550 --> 57:23.090
I rely on you to give me
good example, Marlowe.

57:26.050 --> 57:28.620
[instrumental music]

57:28.820 --> 57:30.970
Who's the frail across the way?

57:31.170 --> 57:32.880
Nothing frail about her, Bernie.

57:41.710 --> 57:46.980
Well, lay low and, uh,
consider another profession.

57:56.510 --> 57:58.960
[music continues]

57:59.160 --> 58:01.300
- Goodnight, miss.
- Goodnight, detective.

58:08.570 --> 58:09.830
Hey.

58:12.440 --> 58:15.930
- Who hurt you?
- Mexicans looking for Peterson.

58:16.130 --> 58:20.010
- What were they looking for?
- For God's sakes, you tell me.

58:26.060 --> 58:28.470
- Coat?
- Thank you.

58:28.670 --> 58:31.500
[music continues]

58:41.030 --> 58:42.520
One could live in
a house like this

58:42.720 --> 58:45.130
and so much would fall away.

58:45.330 --> 58:48.870
That's how the other half lives
and we do pretty good.

58:53.350 --> 59:00.060
Clare, you haven't once told me
why you really want Nico.

59:00.260 --> 59:02.980
Amanda Toxteth claims
that he wasn't

59:03.180 --> 59:05.750
especially thoughtful
in the bedroom.

59:07.670 --> 59:11.500
Poor Amanda,
she played a tough game.

59:12.590 --> 59:15.510
Marlowe: Tell me about it.

59:15.710 --> 59:18.380
There's not one studio in
this town that's run by men

59:18.580 --> 59:21.730
who were looked at twice before
they had their first million.

59:24.640 --> 59:27.130
If women never liked you
when you were poor,

59:27.330 --> 59:29.660
that must twist you all up.

59:29.860 --> 59:33.530
So they call you forth for
refreshing acts of humiliation.

59:33.730 --> 59:36.580
Marlowe: Who did you learn
this from? The Ambassador?

59:36.780 --> 59:40.190
Mm, the Ambassador got to
town already loaded...

59:40.390 --> 59:44.450
and he'll be even richer when he
leaves, just without my mother.

59:44.650 --> 59:46.270
Your mother also wanted Nico.

59:48.140 --> 59:49.580
She tried to hire you too?

59:51.890 --> 59:56.420
She always wants
what I want or have.

59:56.620 --> 59:58.690
You mean Nico?

59:58.890 --> 1:00:03.170
Maybe, or maybe she's just
afraid that you'll make love

1:00:03.370 --> 1:00:07.090
to me before you find out
just how terrible I am.

1:00:07.290 --> 1:00:08.690
That's a terrible idea.

1:00:10.470 --> 1:00:12.960
- Why?
- Why?

1:00:13.160 --> 1:00:16.910
Because I'm in your employ,
because you're half my age.

1:00:19.310 --> 1:00:22.920
Because you're so beautiful
I'd lose my bearings.

1:00:28.270 --> 1:00:31.490
What can we do then,
if we can't do that?

1:00:33.840 --> 1:00:36.720
[instrumental music]

1:00:36.920 --> 1:00:38.590
We can dance.

1:00:44.640 --> 1:00:46.690
Clare: I spent six years
with the nuns,

1:00:46.890 --> 1:00:49.610
just so my mother could
be a flash-eyed colleen

1:00:49.810 --> 1:00:52.040
with her hands on her hips.

1:00:52.240 --> 1:00:56.610
She had to play the virgin
for 15 years, gosh.

1:00:56.810 --> 1:01:00.570
Although you surrender
in each picture, naturally.

1:01:00.770 --> 1:01:02.750
Then all the while,
the ambassador

1:01:02.950 --> 1:01:06.310
was advising her financially.

1:01:08.220 --> 1:01:12.060
Has he ever advised
you financially?

1:01:12.260 --> 1:01:13.750
You mean has he ever touched me?

1:01:15.360 --> 1:01:16.800
Suppose I do.

1:01:19.060 --> 1:01:20.630
Maybe that's the wrong question.

1:01:22.280 --> 1:01:23.730
- Oh!
- Pardon me.

1:01:23.930 --> 1:01:26.690
[chuckles]
You're a terrible dancer.

1:01:26.890 --> 1:01:28.650
I'm a worse lover.

1:01:28.850 --> 1:01:30.680
You expect me to believe that?

1:01:32.950 --> 1:01:35.770
[music continues]

1:01:37.560 --> 1:01:40.690
- The dance is good.
- For now.

1:01:45.700 --> 1:01:49.050
[sighs]
I have to be somewhere.

1:01:53.710 --> 1:01:59.070
Should I come back here after?
Stay over as friends?

1:01:59.270 --> 1:02:01.680
That never works, Clare.

1:02:01.880 --> 1:02:03.540
I don't intend it to.

1:02:08.110 --> 1:02:09.070
No.

1:02:11.720 --> 1:02:13.460
A puzzle has many pieces.

1:02:15.600 --> 1:02:17.950
I don't know exactly
what you're gonna find...

1:02:20.300 --> 1:02:22.390
you might find a dragon
and have to kill it.

1:02:24.080 --> 1:02:25.610
- Fair enough.
- Mm.

1:02:26.610 --> 1:02:29.520
[music continues]

1:02:33.920 --> 1:02:37.410
- Goodnight, Philip Marlowe.
- 'Night.

1:02:37.610 --> 1:02:39.800
♪ At the moon

1:02:40.000 --> 1:02:45.840
♪ But I'll be seeing you

1:02:47.800 --> 1:02:50.720
[engine revving]

1:02:51.940 --> 1:02:58.600
♪ I'll be seeing you ♪

1:03:03.780 --> 1:03:06.690
[ominous music]

1:03:33.810 --> 1:03:36.720
[music continues]

1:03:47.860 --> 1:03:50.780
[thunder rumbling]

1:04:03.840 --> 1:04:06.750
[music continues]

1:04:31.080 --> 1:04:32.040
[door shuts]

1:04:33.870 --> 1:04:36.780
[music continues]

1:04:50.530 --> 1:04:52.800
Clare: Is the ambassador here?
Woman 1: Yes, ma'am.

1:04:56.930 --> 1:04:58.940
Clare: So do we call you
ambassador now?

1:04:59.140 --> 1:05:01.200
Clare, how are you?
It's good to see you.

1:05:03.240 --> 1:05:05.730
- Your mother just left.
- What did she want?

1:05:05.930 --> 1:05:07.780
- Don't ask.
- So it didn't go well?

1:05:07.980 --> 1:05:10.510
[indistinct chatter]

1:05:13.730 --> 1:05:16.310
Where's your camera,
Mr. Marlowe?

1:05:16.510 --> 1:05:17.350
I don't have one.

1:05:17.550 --> 1:05:19.180
Mm, do you have any idea

1:05:19.380 --> 1:05:21.270
how much that photo
would've been worth?

1:05:21.470 --> 1:05:25.350
- Are they breaking any laws?
- Only the laws of attraction.

1:05:27.140 --> 1:05:30.840
I, for one, would pay
big money for an account

1:05:31.040 --> 1:05:33.190
of all of their
terms of endearment.

1:05:35.620 --> 1:05:37.890
He's old enough
to be her father.

1:05:38.090 --> 1:05:39.060
Yeah.

1:05:40.580 --> 1:05:41.510
[chuckles]

1:05:41.710 --> 1:05:44.770
But then, so are you.

1:05:44.970 --> 1:05:47.810
[indistinct chatter]

1:05:54.990 --> 1:05:56.510
There goes Bernie Ohls.

1:05:59.600 --> 1:06:02.010
Arthur ran the number plate
of your visitor last night.

1:06:02.210 --> 1:06:03.920
Yeah.

1:06:04.120 --> 1:06:07.710
That car belongs
to Dorothy Quincannon.

1:06:07.910 --> 1:06:09.970
- So?
- So?

1:06:10.170 --> 1:06:12.970
Of all the people in Los Angeles
who you do not fuck with,

1:06:13.170 --> 1:06:15.800
the new ambassador who opened
the Pacific Studios

1:06:16.000 --> 1:06:19.270
with bootleg money and his
mistress are top of the list!

1:06:21.490 --> 1:06:22.720
[sighs]

1:06:22.920 --> 1:06:24.580
Everybody's better
connected than us.

1:06:26.240 --> 1:06:28.110
Ever wonder what
the attraction was?

1:06:29.810 --> 1:06:32.040
What, the mother
or the daughter?

1:06:32.240 --> 1:06:33.200
Maybe both.

1:06:34.330 --> 1:06:36.560
[scoffs]

1:06:36.760 --> 1:06:38.560
You are a very sick man,
Marlowe.

1:06:38.760 --> 1:06:41.600
[instrumental music on radio]

1:06:45.910 --> 1:06:48.390
LAPD found Lynn Peterson.

1:06:52.480 --> 1:06:54.570
- Where is she?
- Encino.

1:06:56.360 --> 1:06:58.010
She'll wait till we get there.

1:07:03.280 --> 1:07:05.710
Was she, um, was she shot
with my gun?

1:07:07.150 --> 1:07:08.450
No.

1:07:10.370 --> 1:07:12.020
No, she wasn't shot.

1:07:17.120 --> 1:07:20.030
[tense music]

1:07:30.130 --> 1:07:32.360
<i>Man 4: Deep continuous</i>
<i>transverse wound</i>

1:07:32.560 --> 1:07:35.140
<i>to the anterior</i>
<i>triangles of the neck,</i>

1:07:35.340 --> 1:07:38.060
<i>cutting both venous</i>
<i>and arterial structures.</i>

1:07:38.260 --> 1:07:40.760
<i>Injuries not</i>
<i>compatible with life.</i>

1:07:40.960 --> 1:07:42.320
That means her throat was cut.

1:07:42.520 --> 1:07:44.190
Man 4: That was after
the lit cigarettes,

1:07:44.390 --> 1:07:46.880
the knuckle dusters,
the knife, the rape.

1:07:48.150 --> 1:07:49.500
Oh, my God.

1:08:02.940 --> 1:08:05.340
Guys, you're not
gonna like this.

1:08:15.960 --> 1:08:17.750
- Hey, you!
- Yeah?

1:08:17.950 --> 1:08:20.540
That's the sister of the man
you identified two weeks ago

1:08:20.730 --> 1:08:22.930
who was killed outside
the Corbata Club.

1:08:23.130 --> 1:08:25.190
His head was squashed
like a pumpkin.

1:08:25.390 --> 1:08:26.720
Were you aware of that?

1:08:26.910 --> 1:08:28.240
Make a note of it
in your report, doc.

1:08:28.440 --> 1:08:31.240
- I just do the bodies.
- Just make a note of it.

1:08:31.440 --> 1:08:35.110
- Thank you, Bernie.
- Nobody lives forever.

1:08:38.110 --> 1:08:41.300
When things get down and dirty,
rank and file don't like it.

1:08:41.490 --> 1:08:44.770
- Not even in county.
- At last, Bernie.

1:08:47.120 --> 1:08:49.730
Joe? Come with us.

1:08:53.860 --> 1:08:56.010
Bernie: The blue car
came in an hour ago,

1:08:56.210 --> 1:08:59.660
the two suspects
from Tijuana got out.

1:08:59.860 --> 1:09:04.010
- That's the re-spray.
Bernie: Yep. Who's that?

1:09:04.210 --> 1:09:06.670
That's the Bentley of
Mr. Lou Hendricks.

1:09:06.870 --> 1:09:08.840
- <i>The</i>Lou Hendricks.
- The same.

1:09:09.040 --> 1:09:11.980
So he's a member,
like the Mexicans.

1:09:12.180 --> 1:09:13.500
I want you to go
after these fucks

1:09:13.700 --> 1:09:15.460
like a rat terrier in a closet.

1:09:15.660 --> 1:09:17.070
I don't wanna know
anything about it.

1:09:17.270 --> 1:09:18.550
Ah, come on, Bernie,
do it yourself.

1:09:18.750 --> 1:09:21.640
I still have a pension,
you don't.

1:09:21.840 --> 1:09:23.290
Fair enough.

1:09:23.490 --> 1:09:25.820
We own Bay Canyon, we'll block
the roads in and out.

1:09:26.020 --> 1:09:27.910
Give me the glasses.

1:09:28.110 --> 1:09:30.300
- Get down that rat hole.
- How?

1:09:30.500 --> 1:09:33.740
- Doesn't matter how.
- Fair enough.

1:09:33.940 --> 1:09:36.300
Come on, Joe, let's do this.

1:09:45.440 --> 1:09:48.710
- You look like shit.
- Fair enough.

1:09:48.910 --> 1:09:51.450
Just so you know, the real shit
doesn't go down in there until

1:09:51.650 --> 1:09:56.410
the early hours, so once you're
in, you gotta wait and wait.

1:09:56.610 --> 1:09:59.160
Fair enough.

1:09:59.360 --> 1:10:02.160
And remember, you're the guy
who can ID the Mexicans,

1:10:02.360 --> 1:10:04.290
so watch your corners.

1:10:04.490 --> 1:10:05.860
Fair enough.

1:10:06.060 --> 1:10:08.290
Hey, will this
get my badge back?

1:10:09.590 --> 1:10:10.980
Is that what you want?

1:10:13.380 --> 1:10:14.650
You mind?

1:10:14.850 --> 1:10:17.690
[suspenseful music]

1:10:36.310 --> 1:10:37.660
[clanking]

1:10:44.800 --> 1:10:47.720
[music continues]

1:10:58.550 --> 1:11:00.780
- Otis!
- Yes, ma'am?

1:11:00.980 --> 1:11:03.210
- I'll be right down.
Otis: Yes, ma'am.

1:11:07.300 --> 1:11:10.740
You're a long, long way
from Tipperary, Dorothy.

1:11:18.270 --> 1:11:21.180
[suspenseful music]

1:11:44.120 --> 1:11:45.390
What is this called?

1:11:45.590 --> 1:11:48.860
It's called a Miguel Finn,
a Mickey Finn.

1:11:53.040 --> 1:11:55.960
[music continues]

1:11:57.610 --> 1:11:58.570
[door opens]

1:12:23.070 --> 1:12:25.990
[music continues]

1:12:50.710 --> 1:12:52.360
[sniffing]

1:12:55.150 --> 1:12:59.990
Girls, boys, heroin, coke.

1:13:00.190 --> 1:13:01.640
I've given it some thought,

1:13:01.840 --> 1:13:03.550
and I'd like to fill out
an application.

1:13:05.110 --> 1:13:06.650
Not polite.

1:13:06.850 --> 1:13:08.820
Maybe because I don't feel
polite this fine evening.

1:13:09.020 --> 1:13:10.960
Well, let's have a drink,
talk about it.

1:13:11.160 --> 1:13:14.310
- You heard about Lynn Peterson?
- Tragic thing.

1:13:14.510 --> 1:13:16.090
What if I told you that
the police won't touch you,

1:13:16.290 --> 1:13:18.170
but they're expecting
that I will.

1:13:20.000 --> 1:13:23.050
I have nothing to do with
Lynn Peterson or Nico Peterson.

1:13:25.350 --> 1:13:28.760
This is Los Angeles,
people are on the make.

1:13:28.960 --> 1:13:30.710
Why were they here on the make?

1:13:30.910 --> 1:13:33.720
His sister was a Cabana whore
with a junk habit,

1:13:33.920 --> 1:13:35.590
she worked for you,
you're a pimp.

1:13:35.790 --> 1:13:38.240
No, I'm not, I don't control
the place, I'm not the boss.

1:13:38.440 --> 1:13:40.420
So who is?

1:13:40.620 --> 1:13:43.380
Dorothy Quincannon?
The Ambassador?

1:13:43.580 --> 1:13:45.290
How little you know,
Mr. Marlowe.

1:13:45.490 --> 1:13:48.250
I do know a guy
named Lou Hendricks.

1:13:48.450 --> 1:13:51.870
- You might know him too.
- His people call my people.

1:13:52.070 --> 1:13:53.560
I'm going down
the rabbit hole, Floyd,

1:13:53.760 --> 1:13:55.160
I might even take you with me.

1:13:56.510 --> 1:13:59.090
We'll need that drink then.

1:13:59.290 --> 1:14:01.350
We can join
Lou Hendricks down below.

1:14:01.550 --> 1:14:04.440
Beating you round the walls
doesn't get me much does it?

1:14:04.640 --> 1:14:07.400
- Must be the military training.
- Huh?

1:14:07.600 --> 1:14:12.410
- Okay, I'll have that drink.
- It's, uh, very difficult.

1:14:12.610 --> 1:14:15.370
To balance your many obligations
to the various interests

1:14:15.570 --> 1:14:17.630
of all the people,
powerful people.

1:14:17.830 --> 1:14:20.810
Discretion is a thing
that we provide.

1:14:21.010 --> 1:14:23.030
And you take protection
in return.

1:14:23.230 --> 1:14:27.680
Very, very serious protection,
Mr. Marlowe.

1:14:31.460 --> 1:14:33.820
Now you will know
the full extent of it.

1:14:34.020 --> 1:14:37.040
I appreciate your
difficulties, Mr. Hanson.

1:14:37.240 --> 1:14:39.610
It's difficult to run a whore
house and not have anyone know

1:14:39.810 --> 1:14:42.830
it is one... especially
when you're also

1:14:43.030 --> 1:14:45.750
in the narcotics business.

1:14:45.950 --> 1:14:48.050
Floyd: There's an awful lot
you don't understand.

1:14:48.250 --> 1:14:51.090
- About narcotics?
Floyd: About management.

1:14:54.750 --> 1:14:57.020
The Corbata Club investors
leave me alone to,

1:14:57.220 --> 1:14:59.060
to manage the place.

1:14:59.260 --> 1:15:02.500
Now, I don't trouble them
when difficulties arise,

1:15:02.700 --> 1:15:07.030
unless the difficulties are,
how shall we say,

1:15:07.230 --> 1:15:08.940
hard for me to deal with alone.

1:15:09.140 --> 1:15:11.980
[intense music]

1:15:16.070 --> 1:15:19.950
Like the whore
who won't play ball,

1:15:20.150 --> 1:15:24.080
the girl or a boy who aren't
as interested as you'd like.

1:15:27.610 --> 1:15:30.650
Or the snoop
who's far too interested.

1:15:32.700 --> 1:15:34.570
You give them
a little something?

1:15:38.570 --> 1:15:40.530
Are you alright, Mr. Marlowe?

1:15:45.360 --> 1:15:48.360
I would've thought you'd be a
man who could hold his liquor.

1:15:49.760 --> 1:15:51.240
Seems I was wrong.

1:15:57.850 --> 1:16:00.940
As you go to sleep,
I want you to consider...

1:16:03.770 --> 1:16:08.920
the whereabouts of Nico Peterson
were never the issue,

1:16:09.120 --> 1:16:13.140
it was the whereabouts of what
Nico had in his possession.

1:16:13.340 --> 1:16:17.270
We'll get to the bottom of
those issues without your help.

1:16:17.470 --> 1:16:21.230
From everything I hear,
you were never a team player,

1:16:21.430 --> 1:16:25.450
never went along to get along
and see where it gets you?

1:16:27.490 --> 1:16:29.890
You're dying, alone.

1:16:30.090 --> 1:16:32.930
[music continues]

1:16:49.470 --> 1:16:52.390
[instrumental music]

1:17:01.180 --> 1:17:05.580
♪ I'll be seeing you

1:17:05.780 --> 1:17:10.330
♪ In all the
ol' familiar places ♪

1:17:10.520 --> 1:17:14.460
♪ That this heart of mine
embraces ♪

1:17:14.660 --> 1:17:18.590
♪ All day through

1:17:18.790 --> 1:17:22.160
♪ In that small cafe

1:17:22.360 --> 1:17:24.770
[laughing]

1:17:24.970 --> 1:17:27.120
♪ Across the way

1:17:27.320 --> 1:17:31.610
♪ The children's carousel

1:17:31.810 --> 1:17:33.350
♪ The chestnut tress

1:17:33.550 --> 1:17:35.870
♪ The wishing well

1:17:36.070 --> 1:17:39.880
♪ I'll be seeing you

1:17:40.080 --> 1:17:44.010
♪ In every lovely summer's day

1:17:44.210 --> 1:17:48.280
♪ In everything
that's light and gay ♪

1:17:48.480 --> 1:17:52.280
♪ I'll always think of you
that way ♪

1:17:52.480 --> 1:17:56.550
♪ I'll find you
in the morning sun ♪

1:17:56.750 --> 1:18:00.200
♪ And when the night is new

1:18:00.400 --> 1:18:03.250
♪ I'll be looking
at the moon ♪

1:18:03.450 --> 1:18:06.600
♪ But I'll be seeing you

1:18:06.800 --> 1:18:09.640
[music continues]

1:18:31.660 --> 1:18:33.140
- You alright?
- Yeah, I'll be here.

1:18:38.140 --> 1:18:39.190
Damn.

1:18:45.370 --> 1:18:46.720
Cedric: You're awake?

1:18:49.680 --> 1:18:50.900
[coughs]

1:18:53.680 --> 1:18:57.040
- This must be yours.
- You didn't drink it?

1:18:57.240 --> 1:18:59.480
I remembered what happened
to Alice in Wonderland

1:18:59.680 --> 1:19:01.610
when she bit the mushroom.

1:19:01.810 --> 1:19:03.960
- You pretended.
- And you?

1:19:04.160 --> 1:19:07.790
Should've known, who offers
the wheels a cocktail?

1:19:07.990 --> 1:19:09.790
Lou Hendricks?

1:19:09.990 --> 1:19:11.580
They're working him
over real bad.

1:19:11.780 --> 1:19:14.540
That's him shackled up
inside I guess?

1:19:14.740 --> 1:19:16.620
They'll have him
speaking Greek soon.

1:19:18.270 --> 1:19:20.100
[man panting]

1:19:21.060 --> 1:19:22.010
[man groans]

1:19:39.200 --> 1:19:41.080
Promise you never
do that to me.

1:19:43.690 --> 1:19:45.820
If I help you out of here...

1:19:47.430 --> 1:19:48.950
will you help me?

1:19:51.480 --> 1:19:52.830
Fuck yeah.

1:19:57.920 --> 1:19:59.570
Crank up the volume.

1:20:01.700 --> 1:20:04.020
Two dead boys from Tijuana.

1:20:04.220 --> 1:20:06.680
See where this gets ya?

1:20:06.880 --> 1:20:08.240
You're making this hard
for me, Lou.

1:20:08.440 --> 1:20:11.200
<i>[Lecuona Cuban Boys</i>
<i>singing "Cubanacan"]</i>

1:20:11.400 --> 1:20:12.940
[groans]

1:20:13.140 --> 1:20:14.020
[glass clinks]

1:20:15.760 --> 1:20:18.210
Much too hard.

1:20:18.410 --> 1:20:20.380
What else do you do
for Lou Hendricks?

1:20:20.580 --> 1:20:22.510
Too damn much if you ask me.

1:20:26.120 --> 1:20:27.040
[glass shattering]

1:20:27.240 --> 1:20:28.700
[metal clanks]

1:20:28.900 --> 1:20:30.170
[rattling]

1:20:31.910 --> 1:20:33.440
[sighs] Sweet.

1:20:33.640 --> 1:20:35.270
Oh, righteous.

1:20:35.470 --> 1:20:36.660
[thud]

1:20:36.860 --> 1:20:39.840
Hey, we both go in there...

1:20:40.040 --> 1:20:42.620
we're both coming
out alive, yeah?

1:20:42.820 --> 1:20:44.840
Agreed, Mr. Marlowe.

1:20:45.040 --> 1:20:47.850
[music continues]

1:20:48.050 --> 1:20:48.930
[creaking]

1:20:53.370 --> 1:20:56.730
Floyd: I'm getting
awfully sick of this tune.

1:20:56.930 --> 1:20:57.800
[glass clinks]

1:21:01.110 --> 1:21:03.040
Where is she?

1:21:03.240 --> 1:21:05.170
Lou: Where is who?

1:21:05.370 --> 1:21:06.820
The Chiquita bitch!

1:21:07.020 --> 1:21:08.350
The one that you call Serena!

1:21:08.550 --> 1:21:11.440
I already told you,
Nico had his way with her.

1:21:11.640 --> 1:21:12.950
Floyd: Well, what do you
do with this?

1:21:14.470 --> 1:21:16.830
It's just for shaving.

1:21:17.030 --> 1:21:19.010
Ear, nose and throat jobs, huh?

1:21:19.210 --> 1:21:21.320
I have people
who do that for me.

1:21:21.510 --> 1:21:23.100
Oh, do you?
Oh, so do I!

1:21:23.300 --> 1:21:25.010
So do I!

1:21:25.210 --> 1:21:27.580
- Frederick!
Frederick: Yeah!

1:21:27.780 --> 1:21:30.270
Give him an ear and nose
and throat job, in that order.

1:21:32.400 --> 1:21:35.200
Make him tell us
where Serena is.

1:21:35.400 --> 1:21:36.670
Not Serena!

1:21:38.410 --> 1:21:39.900
<i>The</i>Serena!

1:21:40.100 --> 1:21:41.730
<i>The</i>Serena?

1:21:41.930 --> 1:21:44.470
<i>The</i>Serena Ornamental
over there!

1:21:44.670 --> 1:21:47.420
[man singing in
foreign language]

1:21:53.380 --> 1:21:54.820
A plaster mermaid?

1:21:56.340 --> 1:21:57.920
Serena's a fucking mermaid?

1:21:58.120 --> 1:21:59.740
You gotta work on your Spanish!

1:21:59.940 --> 1:22:01.050
Hanson!

1:22:01.250 --> 1:22:02.100
[gunshot]

1:22:02.290 --> 1:22:03.880
[groans]

1:22:04.080 --> 1:22:05.400
Say this in Spanish!

1:22:05.600 --> 1:22:07.540
[gunfire]

1:22:07.730 --> 1:22:09.800
[glass shattering]

1:22:10.000 --> 1:22:11.800
[water gushing]

1:22:12.000 --> 1:22:13.020
Lou: Cedric!

1:22:13.220 --> 1:22:15.020
[glass clinks]

1:22:15.220 --> 1:22:17.020
Cedric, catch it!

1:22:17.220 --> 1:22:19.630
[water gushing]

1:22:19.830 --> 1:22:21.110
Cedric!

1:22:22.930 --> 1:22:24.550
Yes, boss.

1:22:24.750 --> 1:22:29.910
Was it beyond your capabilities
to save the fucking mermaid?

1:22:30.110 --> 1:22:31.650
Sorry, boss.

1:22:31.850 --> 1:22:35.430
You just broke the
Hendricks bank!

1:22:35.630 --> 1:22:36.910
Sorry, boss.

1:22:37.110 --> 1:22:40.050
It'll take you years
to pay me back!

1:22:40.250 --> 1:22:41.920
Mr. Hendricks...

1:22:42.120 --> 1:22:43.480
that's not fair.

1:22:43.680 --> 1:22:46.660
Lou: As the progeny
of sharecroppers, Cedric,

1:22:46.860 --> 1:22:50.450
you should know life isn't fair!

1:22:50.650 --> 1:22:53.490
[gunfire]

1:22:56.100 --> 1:22:57.320
You're right.

1:23:01.060 --> 1:23:02.890
Life isn't fair.

1:23:06.980 --> 1:23:10.690
I expected to
see grease, didn't you?

1:23:10.880 --> 1:23:12.290
Grease and tarantulas.

1:23:16.460 --> 1:23:19.900
But instead, he's entirely
made of soft tissue.

1:23:21.340 --> 1:23:22.300
Go figure.

1:23:24.650 --> 1:23:25.700
Shall we?

1:23:25.900 --> 1:23:30.270
♪ I've found a new baby

1:23:30.470 --> 1:23:33.260
♪ Down the ol' big sea wave

1:23:35.480 --> 1:23:39.800
♪ I've found a new baby

1:23:40.000 --> 1:23:42.890
♪ A new baby

1:23:43.090 --> 1:23:45.810
[scatting]

1:23:46.010 --> 1:23:47.550
♪ Oh

1:23:47.750 --> 1:23:50.590
[scatting continues]

1:23:52.810 --> 1:23:54.860
Bernie: What will I find inside?

1:23:55.060 --> 1:23:56.820
Marlowe: Some dead bodies.

1:23:57.020 --> 1:23:58.600
Bernie: How many?

1:23:58.800 --> 1:24:00.600
Marlowe: I forgot to count.

1:24:00.800 --> 1:24:02.870
Uh, Lou Hendricks.

1:24:03.070 --> 1:24:06.350
Floyd Hanson,
two gentlemen from Tijuana.

1:24:06.550 --> 1:24:09.000
And one busted mermaid.

1:24:09.200 --> 1:24:10.180
A mermaid?

1:24:10.380 --> 1:24:12.140
The Serena Ornamental.

1:24:12.340 --> 1:24:13.910
Packed with Mexican powder.

1:24:14.830 --> 1:24:16.840
Now, very wet.

1:24:17.040 --> 1:24:18.400
And you are?

1:24:19.830 --> 1:24:21.230
I'm his wheels.

1:24:21.430 --> 1:24:24.270
[scatting continues]

1:24:29.150 --> 1:24:30.060
Huh.

1:24:31.760 --> 1:24:33.900
<i>Marlowe: So what now, Cedric?</i>

1:24:34.100 --> 1:24:36.680
Cedric: We both spilled
some significant blood.

1:24:36.880 --> 1:24:38.770
So we should stick together.

1:24:38.970 --> 1:24:41.520
I'll be your driver
for the moment.

1:24:41.710 --> 1:24:45.210
Marlowe: Cedric,
I have my own wheels.

1:24:45.410 --> 1:24:47.170
Cedric: Of course you do...

1:24:47.370 --> 1:24:48.820
but consider the parking.

1:24:54.690 --> 1:24:57.610
[suspenseful music]

1:25:07.050 --> 1:25:08.460
Well, well...

1:25:08.650 --> 1:25:10.580
if it isn't Mr. Nico Peterson.

1:25:13.320 --> 1:25:15.420
So...

1:25:15.620 --> 1:25:17.160
you're not dead.

1:25:17.360 --> 1:25:19.420
You're quite the detective.

1:25:19.620 --> 1:25:21.950
What do you want?

1:25:22.150 --> 1:25:26.470
You've been looking into the
circumstances of my demise.

1:25:26.670 --> 1:25:29.040
My determination for
some time has been that

1:25:29.240 --> 1:25:32.480
reports of your death
were greatly exaggerated.

1:25:32.680 --> 1:25:33.520
[Nico chuckles]

1:25:33.720 --> 1:25:34.870
I'll say.

1:25:35.070 --> 1:25:36.700
But not your sisters.

1:25:36.900 --> 1:25:42.360
My half-sister's, from my
fathers wild days in Acapulco.

1:25:42.560 --> 1:25:45.270
Marlowe: So you won't
be spilling any tears?

1:25:45.470 --> 1:25:47.890
She is dead, I know.

1:25:48.090 --> 1:25:49.880
Marlowe: She did not die
pleasantly.

1:25:51.450 --> 1:25:52.850
I couldn't help that.

1:25:53.050 --> 1:25:54.500
You could help yourself though.

1:25:54.700 --> 1:25:59.110
Well, I happen to have
something everybody wants.

1:25:59.310 --> 1:26:00.940
Marlowe: More dope?

1:26:01.140 --> 1:26:02.770
Much better than dope.

1:26:02.970 --> 1:26:04.240
[chuckles]

1:26:05.720 --> 1:26:07.240
You are all too much for me.

1:26:08.510 --> 1:26:10.420
All I am is a working stiff.

1:26:11.730 --> 1:26:13.870
I need to get to Clare.

1:26:14.070 --> 1:26:17.050
I will do everything in
my power to put you both

1:26:17.250 --> 1:26:19.480
together and never see
any of you again.

1:26:19.680 --> 1:26:21.620
Then give her a message
from me, will you?

1:26:21.810 --> 1:26:24.400
Tell her, I'll meet her in the
studio prop house, tonight

1:26:24.600 --> 1:26:26.270
and I'll have the goods
on the ambassador.

1:26:26.470 --> 1:26:27.620
What have you got on him?

1:26:27.820 --> 1:26:30.360
Just give her the
message, Marlowe.

1:26:30.560 --> 1:26:32.150
There's a few things
I want cleared up

1:26:32.350 --> 1:26:33.450
before we decide anything.

1:26:33.650 --> 1:26:34.760
What do you wanna know?

1:26:34.960 --> 1:26:36.800
The body outside
the Corbata Club.

1:26:37.000 --> 1:26:39.200
A musician who worked the club.

1:26:39.400 --> 1:26:41.160
- Did you kill him?
- No.

1:26:41.360 --> 1:26:43.060
- Did you kill him?
- No.

1:26:46.460 --> 1:26:48.080
Opportune?

1:26:48.280 --> 1:26:50.910
He looked like me,
I like people who look like me.

1:26:51.100 --> 1:26:53.210
What does Dorothy Quincannon
want from you?

1:26:53.410 --> 1:26:55.040
Well, maybe she wants to
fuck with the ambassador

1:26:55.240 --> 1:26:58.300
who's maybe trying to fuck
her daughter, I don't know.

1:26:58.500 --> 1:27:00.300
Put it together, Marlowe,
you're the detective.

1:27:02.390 --> 1:27:06.090
Everyone wants something on
somebody else, it's all just...

1:27:06.290 --> 1:27:07.870
blackmail in the end.

1:27:10.390 --> 1:27:12.270
I'll be in the prop house...

1:27:12.470 --> 1:27:14.760
7:30.

1:27:14.950 --> 1:27:16.570
Tell her I've got
what she wants.

1:27:20.270 --> 1:27:22.980
[instrumental music]

1:27:23.180 --> 1:27:27.420
<i>Clare: I've just realized, this </i>
<i>is my mother's favorite table.</i>

1:27:27.620 --> 1:27:30.120
This is where the ambassador
advises us financially.

1:27:30.320 --> 1:27:31.470
[indistinct chatter]

1:27:31.670 --> 1:27:32.730
You've asked her along?

1:27:32.930 --> 1:27:34.910
Yes, I felt I needed
some advice.

1:27:35.110 --> 1:27:38.300
- Clare: Financial?
- More like professional.

1:27:38.500 --> 1:27:39.610
Mm...

1:27:39.810 --> 1:27:41.560
My, my, my, it's Clare.

1:27:41.760 --> 1:27:43.090
[Dorothy chuckles]

1:27:43.290 --> 1:27:45.920
What a wonderful surprise,
Mr. Marlowe.

1:27:46.120 --> 1:27:47.220
Tea, mother?

1:27:47.420 --> 1:27:49.090
Dorothy: Scalded.

1:27:49.290 --> 1:27:51.230
Let's hope he brewed it right.

1:27:51.430 --> 1:27:54.710
- So a mouse can trot on it.
- So a mouse can trot on it.

1:27:54.910 --> 1:27:56.540
Marlowe: You know I've so
enjoyed our separate meetings

1:27:56.740 --> 1:27:59.410
that I felt the need for us
all to sit together.

1:27:59.610 --> 1:28:02.540
What Mr. Marlowe means,
my dear, is that he thinks

1:28:02.740 --> 1:28:05.110
he's too clever
for the both of us.

1:28:05.310 --> 1:28:07.720
One of you hired me,
the other tried to,

1:28:07.920 --> 1:28:10.250
so you both seem
to want the same thing.

1:28:10.450 --> 1:28:12.420
Nico left you
for a girl, alright.

1:28:12.620 --> 1:28:15.290
A plaster mermaid
full of Mexican powder.

1:28:15.490 --> 1:28:17.030
That's disgusting.

1:28:17.230 --> 1:28:21.000
A subject about which you
claim to know nothing, yes?

1:28:21.190 --> 1:28:23.560
Why don't you cut to the chase?

1:28:23.760 --> 1:28:27.000
And ask her why she hired you.

1:28:27.200 --> 1:28:29.260
To find Nico Peterson.

1:28:29.460 --> 1:28:34.790
Hiring a detective might just
be the best way to suggest...

1:28:34.990 --> 1:28:37.230
she doesn't know where he is.

1:28:37.430 --> 1:28:38.710
Clare: What do you think,
mother?

1:28:38.910 --> 1:28:41.670
I'm keeping him in
a shack in Rosarito?

1:28:41.870 --> 1:28:43.540
Maybe closer.

1:28:43.740 --> 1:28:46.530
Why don't you tell Mr. Marlowe
what you want with him?

1:28:47.970 --> 1:28:51.360
Perhaps I am trying my best...

1:28:52.630 --> 1:28:54.550
to save your reputation.

1:28:54.750 --> 1:28:56.160
[Clare scoffs]

1:28:56.360 --> 1:28:59.990
Well, maybe, it's the
other way around, mother.

1:29:00.190 --> 1:29:02.300
You see, Mr. Marlowe...

1:29:02.500 --> 1:29:04.950
her lover dumped her.

1:29:05.150 --> 1:29:09.650
The Ambassador to England
wants done with tinsel town.

1:29:09.850 --> 1:29:13.870
So she's playing the only role
left for her to play.

1:29:14.070 --> 1:29:15.790
The femme fatale.

1:29:15.990 --> 1:29:18.230
Her very own Medea.

1:29:18.430 --> 1:29:20.320
[chuckles]

1:29:20.520 --> 1:29:22.750
Oh, well!

1:29:22.950 --> 1:29:25.440
It's a role that awaits
us all, my dear.

1:29:27.530 --> 1:29:29.320
[shattering]

1:29:33.410 --> 1:29:34.680
Huh!

1:29:34.880 --> 1:29:36.380
Well...

1:29:36.570 --> 1:29:39.940
You suspected one of us
would do this, but...

1:29:40.140 --> 1:29:41.860
you just didn't know
which one, did you?

1:29:42.060 --> 1:29:45.080
- Would've laid a dollar on you.
- Mm.

1:29:45.280 --> 1:29:47.780
[sighs] You've quite
mastered the technique

1:29:47.980 --> 1:29:50.350
haven't you, Mr. Marlowe...

1:29:50.550 --> 1:29:52.220
of upsetting the women
in your life?

1:29:52.420 --> 1:29:54.040
There are no women in my life.

1:29:54.240 --> 1:29:55.610
[indistinct chatter]

1:29:55.810 --> 1:29:57.700
Well, then follow her.

1:29:57.900 --> 1:29:59.820
She likes older men.

1:30:01.260 --> 1:30:02.580
[exhales]

1:30:02.770 --> 1:30:04.360
Don't worry...

1:30:04.560 --> 1:30:06.790
I'll pay for the mess,
I always do.

1:30:12.050 --> 1:30:13.760
[indistinct chatter]

1:30:13.960 --> 1:30:16.330
Are you okay?

1:30:16.530 --> 1:30:19.770
I don't care that I'm
less than you think I am.

1:30:19.970 --> 1:30:22.070
I'm always less than
people think I am.

1:30:22.270 --> 1:30:23.420
[whistle blows in distance]

1:30:23.620 --> 1:30:25.380
You're one of those
people who's just

1:30:25.580 --> 1:30:27.680
lucky to be more
than we think you are.

1:30:29.510 --> 1:30:32.000
I'll send you the balance
of what I owe you.

1:30:32.200 --> 1:30:33.950
Maybe I can charge your mother?

1:30:34.150 --> 1:30:36.570
- Together with a finder's fee.
- A what?

1:30:36.770 --> 1:30:38.920
I found him, this afternoon.

1:30:39.120 --> 1:30:40.660
Or rather, he found me.

1:30:40.860 --> 1:30:43.090
I walked into my little house
and there he was.

1:30:43.290 --> 1:30:46.750
- Mr. Nico Peterson.
- Where's he now?

1:30:46.950 --> 1:30:50.360
He'll be waiting for you at the
prop house at Pacific Studios.

1:30:50.560 --> 1:30:53.320
- 7:30 p.m.
- Why the prop house?

1:30:53.520 --> 1:30:55.010
I was hoping you would tell me.

1:30:57.100 --> 1:30:58.200
Clare: Taxi!

1:30:58.400 --> 1:30:59.270
[brakes squeal]

1:31:01.190 --> 1:31:02.160
Go!

1:31:02.360 --> 1:31:04.670
[engine revving]

1:31:05.590 --> 1:31:08.070
[dramatic music]

1:31:11.810 --> 1:31:13.560
Cedric: A car is more
than a vehicle

1:31:13.760 --> 1:31:16.210
Mr. Hendricks used to tell me.

1:31:16.410 --> 1:31:18.480
It's a sealed confessional.

1:31:18.680 --> 1:31:20.960
A repository of secrets.

1:31:21.160 --> 1:31:23.700
And this city,
devoted as it is

1:31:23.900 --> 1:31:26.050
to the internal
combustion engine

1:31:26.250 --> 1:31:28.700
is a city of motorized secrets.

1:31:28.900 --> 1:31:31.750
You're waxing
philosophical, Cedric.

1:31:31.950 --> 1:31:33.230
You have to forgive me,
Mr. Marlowe.

1:31:33.430 --> 1:31:36.230
It's a habit I inherited
from my late employer.

1:31:36.430 --> 1:31:40.670
He had a tendency to digress,
but you did say the prop house?

1:31:40.870 --> 1:31:41.940
I did.

1:31:42.130 --> 1:31:43.240
[music continues]

1:31:43.440 --> 1:31:45.850
And I have to ask myself...

1:31:46.050 --> 1:31:47.590
why the prop house?

1:31:47.790 --> 1:31:50.900
And now you have to tell me,
Cedric, why the prop house?

1:31:51.100 --> 1:31:53.510
[gun cocking]

1:31:53.710 --> 1:31:56.730
<i>Cedric: Nico Peterson was</i>
<i>moving Lou Hendricks' product</i>

1:31:56.930 --> 1:31:59.040
<i>through the prop</i>
<i>house for years.</i>

1:31:59.240 --> 1:32:02.430
<i>Marlowe: And the product</i>
<i>is from Tijuana, hmm?</i>

1:32:02.630 --> 1:32:06.260
<i>Cedric: Hidden in a plaster</i>
<i>raven, the bust of Nefertiti.</i>

1:32:06.460 --> 1:32:08.920
<i>A Virgin of Guadeloupe or a...</i>

1:32:09.120 --> 1:32:11.970
<i>Serena Ornamental.</i>

1:32:12.160 --> 1:32:14.970
You see Mr. Hitchcock,
who could've worked wonders

1:32:15.170 --> 1:32:19.100
for Pacific Pictures,
but is sadly on his way to MGM.

1:32:19.300 --> 1:32:21.580
Mr. Hitchcock,
like Mr. Hendricks,

1:32:21.780 --> 1:32:24.400
always liked to keep
the script to himself.

1:32:26.140 --> 1:32:28.630
But many conversations,

1:32:28.830 --> 1:32:32.030
overheard from this here
front seat, enabled me to do

1:32:32.230 --> 1:32:35.410
what Mr. Hitchcock
always managed so adroitly...

1:32:36.680 --> 1:32:38.080
to work out the plot.

1:32:38.280 --> 1:32:40.860
[gunfire]

1:32:41.060 --> 1:32:43.950
<i>It was never really</i>
<i>about a mermaid.</i>

1:32:44.150 --> 1:32:45.170
<i>It was always</i>
<i>about the contents</i>

1:32:45.370 --> 1:32:47.170
<i>of a certain briefcase,</i>

1:32:47.370 --> 1:32:50.120
<i>which could bring</i>
<i>a whole studio down.</i>

1:32:53.610 --> 1:32:56.520
[suspenseful music]

1:32:58.310 --> 1:32:59.530
Nico: Clare.

1:32:59.730 --> 1:33:00.610
Nico.

1:33:01.830 --> 1:33:03.320
You're on your own?

1:33:03.520 --> 1:33:06.410
Did you want the full
auction house, Nico?

1:33:06.610 --> 1:33:08.200
Me, my mother...

1:33:08.390 --> 1:33:11.070
Floyd Hanson, Lou Hendricks?

1:33:11.270 --> 1:33:13.720
That would be difficult,
two of them are dead.

1:33:13.920 --> 1:33:16.770
Well, you're gonna have
to start the bidding with me.

1:33:16.970 --> 1:33:20.290
What I've got here
is worth a fortune.

1:33:20.490 --> 1:33:22.340
Clare: Really?

1:33:22.540 --> 1:33:23.940
You better show me then.

1:33:27.030 --> 1:33:29.430
All of the records...

1:33:29.630 --> 1:33:32.250
of the heroin which was
flowing through his studio.

1:33:35.780 --> 1:33:38.230
It's more than enough to ruin
the ambassador's reputation,

1:33:38.420 --> 1:33:41.100
and the reputation
of Pacific Pictures.

1:33:41.300 --> 1:33:42.930
<i>Cedric: Nico Peterson</i>
<i>went missing</i>

1:33:43.130 --> 1:33:47.060
<i>with one Serena Ornamental</i>
<i>and one handmade briefcase</i>

1:33:47.260 --> 1:33:49.580
<i>packed with records</i>
<i>of every dope transaction</i>

1:33:49.780 --> 1:33:53.280
<i>since he and Lou Hendricks</i>
<i>started business.</i>

1:33:53.480 --> 1:33:55.460
<i>He was trying to</i>
<i>sell this information</i>

1:33:55.660 --> 1:33:57.370
<i>to anyone he could find.</i>

1:33:59.410 --> 1:34:01.160
[brakes squeal]

1:34:01.360 --> 1:34:04.250
Nico: I'm a book-keeper,
darling, a good one.

1:34:04.450 --> 1:34:07.560
Import, export,
I kept every transaction.

1:34:07.760 --> 1:34:10.560
[engine sputtering]

1:34:10.760 --> 1:34:12.600
[music continues]

1:34:14.340 --> 1:34:17.390
You're more than
a book-keeper, Nico.

1:34:17.590 --> 1:34:19.520
You'd sell tickets
to the gates of hell.

1:34:20.910 --> 1:34:23.620
Nico: Maybe that's why
you like me.

1:34:23.820 --> 1:34:27.060
I never liked you, Nico.

1:34:27.260 --> 1:34:28.620
[metal clanks]

1:34:28.820 --> 1:34:30.060
[gunshot]

1:34:30.260 --> 1:34:31.630
Do you trust me
that little, Clare?

1:34:31.830 --> 1:34:33.150
[gunshot]

1:34:33.350 --> 1:34:35.760
Clare: You know how
it is these days, Nico.

1:34:35.960 --> 1:34:37.360
Nobody trusts anyone.

1:34:38.890 --> 1:34:40.640
What-- what was
that sound, Clare?

1:34:40.840 --> 1:34:42.380
My mother's gun.

1:34:42.580 --> 1:34:44.030
I found it in her boudoir.

1:34:44.230 --> 1:34:45.120
[gunshot]

1:34:45.320 --> 1:34:46.950
Ah, fuck!

1:34:47.150 --> 1:34:49.300
I'm so bad with these.

1:34:49.500 --> 1:34:50.650
Why are you doing this?

1:34:50.850 --> 1:34:52.820
You've always played
too low, Nico.

1:34:53.020 --> 1:34:55.650
Take a lesson from me
and go straight to the top.

1:34:55.850 --> 1:34:56.910
[gunshots]

1:34:57.110 --> 1:34:58.350
Clare: That's better.

1:34:58.550 --> 1:34:59.740
[gunshots]

1:34:59.940 --> 1:35:00.820
Ah!

1:35:03.650 --> 1:35:04.610
[Nico groans]

1:35:06.170 --> 1:35:09.090
[Nico coughs]

1:35:10.920 --> 1:35:12.580
[glass shattering]

1:35:12.780 --> 1:35:13.970
[fire crackling]

1:35:14.170 --> 1:35:16.530
[Nico screams]

1:35:18.970 --> 1:35:22.160
I'm burning your books, Nico.

1:35:22.350 --> 1:35:23.900
[heavy breathing]

1:35:24.100 --> 1:35:24.980
[clanks]

1:35:26.020 --> 1:35:28.810
[fire crackling]

1:35:34.330 --> 1:35:36.290
Is he dead, Mr. Marlowe?

1:35:37.420 --> 1:35:38.380
At last.

1:35:39.820 --> 1:35:41.780
And that's why you hired me?

1:35:41.980 --> 1:35:43.390
So you could finally kill him?

1:35:43.590 --> 1:35:45.000
[fire crackling]

1:35:45.200 --> 1:35:47.140
It's one of the reasons.

1:35:47.340 --> 1:35:49.490
Has the ambassador paid you off?

1:35:49.690 --> 1:35:51.270
I imagine he'll have
to after this

1:35:51.470 --> 1:35:53.010
little piece of spring cleaning.

1:35:53.210 --> 1:35:54.920
[fire crackling]

1:35:57.310 --> 1:35:59.920
Tell me why
I shouldn't shop you.

1:36:03.580 --> 1:36:06.420
Because he was
far too young for me?

1:36:06.620 --> 1:36:08.150
Because he was evil incarnate?

1:36:09.850 --> 1:36:11.150
Because he was already dead.

1:36:13.460 --> 1:36:14.980
Let me deep six this.

1:36:19.420 --> 1:36:20.900
Use the side door.

1:36:29.950 --> 1:36:31.560
Goodbye, Clare Cavendish.

1:36:34.480 --> 1:36:37.010
Good evening, Mr. Marlowe.

1:36:37.210 --> 1:36:40.020
[instrumental music]

1:36:40.220 --> 1:36:43.050
[fire crackling]

1:36:50.320 --> 1:36:53.240
[sirens wailing in distance]

1:36:57.760 --> 1:37:00.160
[instrumental music]

1:37:01.330 --> 1:37:03.680
[sirens wailing]

1:37:09.560 --> 1:37:11.910
[indistinct yelling]

1:37:14.610 --> 1:37:17.520
[clamoring]

1:37:21.530 --> 1:37:24.100
Tell me you didn't
set that fire, Marlowe.

1:37:24.300 --> 1:37:26.580
No, Bernie, you know
I only put 'em out.

1:37:26.780 --> 1:37:28.540
